{"title_page": "Monarchies in the Americas", "text_new": "{{about||the former Kingdom of Hawaii and other Pacific Ocean monarchies|Monarchies in Oceania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:Monarchies of America2.png|thumb|right|{{legend|#A51645|American [[monarchy|monarchies]]}}\n{{legend|#ff6ea7|Non-American monarchies}}{{legend|#967bff|Former monarchies with [[pretender]]s}}]]\n[[File:Crown of Saint Edward (Heraldry).svg|thumb|right|[[St. Edward's Crown]], a part of the [[British Crown Jewels]], is used in the heraldry of those American states with Queen [[Elizabeth II]] as sovereign.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/fr-rf/drap-pers-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion > The Canadian Monarchy > The Queen's Personal Canadian Flag| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| authorlink=Royal Household#The Royal Household of the United Kingdom| journal=Royal Insight Magazine| title=Mailbox| issue=September 2006| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| location=London| url=http://www.royalinsight.gov.uk/output/Page5467.asp| accessdate=1 December 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119134240/http://www.royalinsight.gov.uk/output/Page5467.asp| archivedate=19 November 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\n\nThere are 13 '''monarchies in the Americas''' ([[Self-governance|self-governing]] states and territories that have a [[monarch]] as [[head of state]]). Each is a [[constitutional monarchy]], wherein the sovereign inherits his or her office, usually keeping it until death or [[abdication]], and is bound by laws and customs in the exercise of their powers. Ten of these monarchies are independent states; they equally share Queen [[Elizabeth II]], who resides primarily in the [[United Kingdom]], as their respective sovereign, making them part of a global group known as the [[Commonwealth realm]]s. The others are [[dependent territory|dependencies]] of three European monarchies. As such, none of the monarchies in the [[Americas]] have a permanently residing monarch.\n\nThese crowns continue a history of monarchy in the Americas that reaches back to before [[European colonization of the Americas|European colonization]]. Both tribal and more complex [[pre-Columbian]] societies existed under monarchical forms of government, with some expanding to form vast [[empire]]s under a central [[Monarch|king]] figure, while others did the same with a decentralized collection of tribal regions under a hereditary [[Tribal chief|chieftain]]. None of the contemporary monarchies, however, are descended from those pre-colonial royal systems, instead either having their historical roots in, or still being a part of, the current [[Monarchies in Europe|European monarchies]] that spread their reach across the [[Atlantic Ocean]], beginning in the mid 14th century.\n\nFrom that date on, through the [[Age of Discovery]], European colonization brought extensive American territory under the control of Europe's monarchs, though the majority of these colonies subsequently gained independence from their rulers. Some did so via armed conflict with their mother countries, as in the [[American Revolution]] and the [[Latin American wars of independence]], usually severing all ties to the overseas monarchies in the process. Others gained full sovereignty by legislative paths, such as [[Canada]]'s [[patriation]] of its constitution from the [[United Kingdom]]. A certain number of former colonies became [[republic]]s immediately upon achieving self-governance. The remainder continued with [[Endemism|endemic]] constitutional monarchies\u2014in the cases of [[Haiti]], [[Mexico]], and [[Brazil]]\u2014with their own resident monarch and, for places such as Canada and some island states in the [[Caribbean]], sharing their monarch with their former [[metropole]], the most recently created being [[Monarchy of Belize|that of Belize]] in 1981.\n\n==Current monarchies==\n===American monarchies===\n{{main|Lists of monarchs in the Americas}}\nWhile the incumbent of each of the American monarchies is the same person and resides predominantly in Europe, each of the states are [[Sovereignty|sovereign]] and thus have distinct local monarchies [[Seat (legal entity)|seated]] in their respective [[Capital (political)|capital]]s, with the monarch's day-to-day governmental and ceremonial duties generally carried out by an appointed local [[viceroy]].\n\n====Antigua and Barbuda====\n{{main|Monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda}}\nThe monarchy of [[Antigua and Barbuda]] has its roots in the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish monarchy]], under the authority of which the islands were first colonized in the late 15th century, and later the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British monarchy]], as a [[Crown colony]]. On 1 November 1981, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Antigua and Barbuda|Governor-General of Antigua and Barbuda]], Sir [[Rodney Williams (governor-general)|Rodney Williams]].<ref name=FCO>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/antigua-barbuda| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Antigua and Barbuda| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119085209/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/antigua-barbuda| archive-date=19 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nElizabeth and her [[Prince consort|royal consort]], [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], included Antigua and Barbuda in their 1966 [[Caribbean]] tour, and again in [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|the Queen's Silver Jubilee]] tour of October 1977. Elizabeth returned once more in 1985.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| title=The  Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean realms| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> For the country's 25th anniversary of independence, on 30 October 2006, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], opened Antigua and Barbuda's new parliament building, reading a message from his mother, the Queen. The Duke of York visited Antigua and Barbuda in January 2001.<ref name=FCO />\n\n====The Bahamas====\n{{main|Monarchy of The Bahamas}}\nThe monarchy of [[The Bahamas]] has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonized in the late 15th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony, after 1717. On 10 July 1973, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bahamas.gov.bs/bahamasweb2/home.nsf/vContentW/AD50C97FCEE345FE06256F02007F60C0| last=Government of the Bahamas| authorlink1=Politics of the Bahamas| title=The Government of the Bahamas > About The Government > Overview and Structure of the Government| publisher=Government of the Bahamas| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of The Bahamas. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of the Bahamas|Governor-General of the Bahamas]], Sir [[Cornelius A. Smith]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bahamaspress.com/2019/06/17/the-cabinet-office-announces-the-honourable-cornelius-a-smith-to-serve-as-the-11th-governor-general-in-an-independent-bahamas/|title=The Cabinet Office announces The Honourable Cornelius A. Smith to serve as the 11th Governor-General in an Independent Bahamas! {{!}} Bahamaspress.com|last=media|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n====Barbados====\n{{main|Monarchy of Barbados}}\nThe monarchy of Barbados has its roots in the [[Monarchy of England|English monarchy]], under the authority of which the island was claimed in 1625 and first colonized in 1627,<ref name=BParlHist>{{cite web| url=http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php| last=The Clerk Of Parliament| title=The Barbados Parliament > Parliament's History| publisher=Parliament of Barbados| accessdate=1 December 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523083154/http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php| archivedate=23 May 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and later the British monarchy. By the 18th century, Barbados became one of the main seats of the British Crown's authority in the [[British West Indies]], and then, after an attempt in 1958 at [[West Indies Federation|a federation with other West Indian colonies]], continued as a [[self-governing colony]] until, on 30 November 1966, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Barbados. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Barbados|Governor-General of Barbados]], Sir [[Elliott Belgrave]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.barbados.gov.bb/gg.htm| last=Government Information Service| title=Government > Governor General| publisher=Government of Barbados| accessdate=5 January 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081118142029/http://www.barbados.gov.bb/gg.htm <!--Added by H3llBot-->| archivedate=18 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, Elizabeth's cousin, [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent]], opened the second session of the first parliament of the newly established country,<ref name=BParlHist /> before the Queen herself, along with Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, toured Barbados. Elizabeth returned for her Silver Jubilee in 1977, and again in 1989, to mark the 350th anniversary of the establishment of the Barbadian parliament.<ref name=BParlHist /><ref name=Buck1>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| title=The Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean Realms| publisher=Her Majesty\u2019s Stationery Office| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Barbados|Prime Minister]] [[Owen Arthur]] called for a referendum on Barbados becoming a republic to be held in 2005,<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas |first=Norman |title=Barbados to vote on move to republic |publisher=Caribbean News |date=7 February 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/02/07/vote.shtml |accessdate=1 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228082001/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/02/07/vote.shtml |archivedate=28 December 2007 }}</ref> though the vote was then pushed back to \"at least 2006\" in order to speed up Barbados' integration in the [[CARICOM Single Market and Economy]]. It was announced on 26 November 2007 that [[Barbadian republic referendum|the referendum]] would be held in 2008, together with the [[Barbadian general election, 2008|general election that year]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Staff| title=Referendum on Republic to be bundled with election| publisher=Caribbean Broadcasting Corporation| date=26 November 2007| url=http://www.evernetcorp.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=13417| accessdate=27 November 2007}}</ref> The vote was, however, postponed again to a later point, due to administrative concerns.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Gollop |title=Vote Off |url=http://www.nationnews.com/story/317791120649409.php |publisher=The Nation |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=22 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228045102/http://www.nationnews.com/story/317791120649409.php |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Belize====\n{{main|Monarchy of Belize}}\nBelize was, until the 15th century, a part of the [[Maya civilization|Mayan Empire]], containing smaller states headed by a hereditary ruler known as an ''[[ajaw]]'' (later ''k\u2019uhul ajaw'').{{#tag:ref|Both terms appear in early Colonial texts (including ''Papeles de Paxbol\u00f3n'') where they are used as synonymous to Aztec and Spanish terms for supreme rulers and their domains \u2013 ''tlahtoani'' (''[[Tlatoani]]'') and ''tlahtocayotl'', ''rey'', or ''magestad'' and ''reino'', ''se\u00f1or'' and ''se\u00f1or\u00edo'', or ''dominio''.|group=N|name=Maya1}} The present monarchy of Belize has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the area was first colonised in the 16th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 21 September 1981, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Belize.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.governmentofbelize.gov.bz/ab_politics.html| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421070007/http://www.governmentofbelize.gov.bz/ab_politics.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=21 April 2008| last=Government of Belize| authorlink=Politics of Belize| title=About Belize > Politics > Constitution and Government| publisher=Government of Belize| accessdate=5 January 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Belize|Governor-General of Belize]], Sir [[Colville Young]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/belize| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Belize| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222205656/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/belize/| archive-date=22 December 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\n{{main|Monarchy of Canada}}\n[[File:Mohawk-kings.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Painting of the [[Four Mohawk Kings]], done during their visit with Queen [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]] in 1710]]\n[[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canada's aboriginal peoples]] had systems of governance organised in a fashion similar to the [[Western world|Occidental]] concept of monarchy;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldandi.com/specialreport/2001/october/Sa21577.htm |last=Kehoe |first=Alice Beck |title=First Nations History |publisher=The World & I Online |date=October 2001 |accessdate=2 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610234600/http://www.worldandi.com/specialreport/2001/october/Sa21577.htm |archivedate=10 June 2011 }}</ref> European explorers often referred to hereditary leaders of tribes as kings.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pequotmuseum.org/Home/CrossPaths/CrossPathsFall2002/JohnSimonsEngravingsoftheFourKingsMoreThanMeetstheEye.htm| last=Simon| first=John| title=Engravings of the Four Kings: More Than Meets the Eye| publisher=Pequot Museum| accessdate=1 January 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121184743/http://www.pequotmuseum.org/Home/CrossPaths/CrossPathsFall2002/JohnSimonsEngravingsoftheFourKingsMoreThanMeetstheEye.htm| archivedate=21 November 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The present monarchy of Canada has its roots in the [[List of French monarchs|French]] and English monarchies, under the authority of which the area was colonised in the 16th-18th centuries, and later the British monarchy. The country became a self-governing confederation on 1 July 1867, recognised as a kingdom in its own right,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/publctn/101/102-eng.cfm |last=Department of Canadian Heritage |authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage |title=The Crown in Canada |publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada |accessdate=2 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210231140/http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/publctn/101/102-eng.cfm |archivedate=10 December 2014 }}</ref> but did not have full legislative autonomy from the British Crown until the passage of the [[Statute of Westminster 1931|Statute of Westminster]] on 11 December 1931,<ref name=COM>{{cite book| last=MacLeod| first=Kevin S.| title=A Crown of Maples: Constitutional Monarchy in Canada| publisher=Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Canada| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/fr-rf/crnCdn/crn_mpls-eng.pdf| isbn=978-0-662-46012-1| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> retaining the then reigning monarch, [[George V]], as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Canada. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[Governor General of Canada]], [[Julie Payette]], and in each of the provinces by a [[Lieutenant-Governor (Canada)|lieutenant governor]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mun.ca/govhouse/duties.html| last=Government House| authorlink=Government House (Newfoundland and Labrador)| title=Role and duties of the Lieutenant-Governor| publisher=Memorial University| accessdate=18 January 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080223001655/http://www.mun.ca/govhouse/duties.html |archivedate = 23 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Grenada====\n{{main|Monarchy of Grenada}}\nThe monarchy of [[Grenada]] has its roots in the French monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the mid 17th century, and later the English and then British monarchy, as a Crown colony.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/grenada?profile=history&pg=3| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Grenada| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121132511/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/grenada?profile=history&pg=3| archive-date=21 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 February 1974, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Grenada. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Grenada|Governor-General of Grenada]], currently Dame [[C\u00e9cile La Grenade]].<ref name=britannica>{{cite encyclopedia| title=Grenada| encyclopedia=Britannica Online Encyclopedia| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/245745/Grenada| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Jamaica====\n{{main|Monarchy of Jamaica}}\n[[File:Charles Camilla Jamaica 2008.jpg|thumb|right|[[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles, Prince of Wales]] (far left), heir to the [[Monarchy of Jamaica|Jamaican throne]], and his wife, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] (centre), at the Half Moon Hotel, [[Montego Bay]], 13 March 2008]]\nThe monarchy of [[Jamaica]] has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the late 16th century, and later the English and then British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 6 August 1962, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Jamaica. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[Governor-General of Jamaica]], Sir [[Patrick Allen (Governor-General)|Patrick Allen]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/jamaica| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Jamaica| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119142220/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/jamaica| archive-date=19 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Jamaica]] [[Portia Simpson-Miller]] has expressed an intention to oversee the process required to change Jamaica to a republic by 2012; she originally stated this would be complete by August of that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamaica plans to become a republic|url=http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=702384&vId=|accessdate=31 December 2011|newspaper=Sky News Australia|date=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jamaica to break links with Queen, says Prime Minister Simpson Miller|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-16449969|accessdate=8 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 January 2012}}</ref> In 2003, former Prime Minister [[P.J. Patterson]], advocated making Jamaica into a republic by 2007.<ref name=republic>{{cite news| last=Staff| title=Jamaica eyes republican future| publisher=BBC| date=22 September 2003| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/3127742.stm| accessdate=14 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Kitts and Nevis====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\nThe monarchy of [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] has its roots in the English and French monarchies, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the early 17th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 10 June 1973, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.kn/ct.asp?xItem=462&CtNode=58&mp=1|title=About Government|accessdate=18 December 2008|publisher=Government of Saint Kitts and Nevis|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211101312/http://www.gov.kn/ct.asp?xItem=462&CtNode=58&mp=1|archivedate=11 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Kitts and Nevis|Governor-General of Saint Kitts and Nevis]], currently Sir [[Tapley Seaton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-kitts-nevis|title=Country Profile: Saint Kitts and Nevis|accessdate=18 December 2008|work=|publisher=Foreign and Commonwealth Office (UK)|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209005725/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-kitts-nevis|archive-date=9 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Lucia====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Lucia}}\nThe [[Island Caribs|Caribs]] who occupied the island of [[Saint Lucia]] in pre-Columbian times had a complex society, with hereditary kings and shamans. The present monarchy has its roots in the [[Monarchy of the Netherlands|Dutch]], French, and English monarchies, under the authority of which the island was first colonised in 1605, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 22 February 1979, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Saint Lucia.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-lucia?profile=history&pg=3| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Saint Lucia| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=1 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121142143/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-lucia?profile=history&pg=3| archive-date=21 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Lucia|Governor-General of Saint Lucia]], currently Dame [[Pearlette Louisy]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.stlucia.gov.lc/agencies/office_of_the_governor_general.htm| last=Government Information Service| title=Government of Saint Lucia > Office of the Governor General| publisher=Government of Saint Lucia| accessdate=1 January 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428015619/http://www.stlucia.gov.lc/agencies/office_of_the_governor_general.htm| archivedate=28 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Vincent and the Grenadines====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\nThe present monarchy of [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] has its roots in the French monarchy, under the authority of which the island was first colonised in 1719, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 27 October 1979, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| title=The Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean Realms| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|Governor-General of Vincent and the Grenadines]], currently Sir [[Frederick Ballantyne]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-vincent-grenadines| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Saint Vincent and the Grenadines| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205032124/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-vincent-grenadines| archive-date=5 December 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Settled monarchies===\n====Denmark====\n{{main|Monarchy of Denmark}}\n[[File:HakonTheOldAndSkule-Flateyjarbok.jpg|thumb|right|H\u00e1kon, King of Norway (seated on the left) took possession of Greenland in 1261.]]\n[[Greenland]] is one of the three [[Countries of the Kingdom of Denmark|constituent countries]] of the [[Kingdom of Denmark]], with [[Margrethe II of Denmark|Queen Margrethe II]] as the reigning sovereign. The territory first came under monarchical rule in 1261, when the populace accepted the overlordship of the [[Monarchy of Norway|King of Norway]]; by 1380, Norway had entered into a [[personal union]] with the Kingdom of Denmark, which became more entrenched with the union of the kingdoms into [[Denmark\u2013Norway]] in 1536. After the dissolution of this arrangement in 1814, Greenland remained as a Danish colony, and, after [[Greenland in World War II|its role in World War II]], was granted its special status within the Kingdom of Denmark in 1953. The monarch is represented in the territory by the ''[[List of Danish High Commissioners in Greenland|Rigsombudsmand]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stm.dk/Index/dokumenter.asp?o=71&n=1&d=1037&s=2&str=stor |title=Home Rule Act of the Faroe Islands |accessdate=5 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Prime Minister of Denmark |date=}}</ref> ([[High Commissioner]]), [[Mikaela Engell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/print/gl.html |title=Greenland |accessdate=15 January 2009 |work= |publisher=CIA World Factbook |date=}}</ref>\n\n====Netherlands====\n{{main|Monarchy of the Netherlands}}\n[[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Sint Maarten]] are constituent countries of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] and thus have [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|King Willem-Alexander]] as their sovereign, as do the islands of the [[Caribbean Netherlands]]. Aruba was first settled under the authority of the Spanish Crown circa 1499, but was acquired by the Dutch in 1634, under whose control the island has remained, save for an interval between 1805 and 1816, when Aruba was captured by the [[Royal Navy]] of [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]]. The former [[Netherlands Antilles]] were originally discovered by explorers sent in the 1490s by the King of Spain, but were eventually conquered by the [[Dutch West India Company]] in the 17th century, whereafter the islands remained under the control of the Dutch Crown as colonial territories. The Netherlands Antilles achieved the status of an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1954, from which Aruba was split in 1986 as a separate constituent country of the larger kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574919/aruba.html|title=Aruba|accessdate=1 January 2009|publisher=MSN Encarta|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kx8ZpKD5?url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574919/aruba.html|archivedate=1 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The former Netherlands Antilles was dissolved in 2010; two of its islands became constituent countries in their own right ([[Governor of Cura\u00e7ao|Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Sint Maarten]]), while the other three became integral parts of the [[Netherlands]] (i.e., the Caribbean Netherlands). The monarch is represented in the constituent countries by the [[Governor of Aruba]], [[Alfonso Boekhoudt]], the [[Governor of Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Frits Goedgedrag]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gouverneur.an/index.php?lang=en|title=Who is Governor Frits Goedgedrag?|accessdate=1 January 2009|publisher=Official Website of the Governor of the Netherlands Antilles|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930121255/http://www.gouverneur.an/index.php?lang=en|archivedate=30 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[Governor of Sint Maarten]], [[Eugene Holiday]].\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{main|Monarchy of the United Kingdom}}\nThe United Kingdom possesses a number of [[British overseas territories|overseas territories]] in the Americas, for whom Queen [[Elizabeth II]] is monarch. In North America are [[Anguilla]], [[Bermuda]], the [[British Virgin Islands]], the [[Cayman Islands]], [[Montserrat]], and the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]], while the [[Falkland Islands]], and [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] are located in South America. The [[Caribbean]] islands were colonised under the authority or the direct instruction of a number of European monarchs, mostly [[Monarchy of England|English]], [[Monarchy of the Netherlands|Dutch]], or [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish]], throughout the first half of the 17th century. By 1681, however, when the Turks and Caicos Islands were settled by Britons, all of the above-mentioned islands were under the control of [[Charles II of England|Charles II of England, Scotland, France and Ireland]]. Colonies were merged and split through various reorganizations of the Crown's Caribbean regions, until 19 December 1980, the date that Anguilla became a British Crown territory in its own right. The monarch is represented in these jurisdictions by: the [[Governor of Anguilla]], [[Tim Foy]]; the [[Governor of Bermuda]], [[John Rankin (diplomat)|John Rankin]]; the [[Governor of the British Virgin Islands]], [[Augustus Jaspert|Gus Jaspert]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukinbvi.fco.gov.uk/en/about-us/hm-governor |title=HM Governor |accessdate=5 January 2009 |work= |publisher=HM Government of the British Virgin Islands |date=}}</ref> the [[Governor of the Cayman Islands]], [[Helen Kilpatrick]]; the [[Governor of Montserrat]], [[Andrew Pearce (diplomat)|Andrew Pearce]]; and the [[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands]], [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]].\n\nThe Falkland Islands, off the south coast of [[Argentina]], were simultaneously claimed for [[Louis XV of France]], in 1764, and [[George III of the United Kingdom]], in 1765, though the French colony was ceded to [[Charles III of Spain]] in 1767. By 1833, however, the islands were under full British control. The South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands were discovered by Captain [[James Cook]] for George III in January 1775, and from 1843 were governed by the British Crown-in-Council through the Falkland Islands, an arrangement that stood until the South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands were incorporated as a distinct British overseas territory in 1985. The monarch is represented in these regions by [[Nigel Phillips]], who is both the [[Governor of the Falkland Islands]] and the [[Commissioner for South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Falklands' Swearing in Ceremony for Governor Phillips on 12 September |first= |last= |newspaper=[[MercoPress]] |date= 2017-09-02 |url=http://en.mercopress.com/2017/09/02/falklands-swearing-in-ceremony-for-governor-phillips-on-12-september |accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Succession laws==\n[[File:Succession America.png|thumb|right|\n{{legend|#C89600|[[Primogeniture#Absolute cognatic primogeniture|absolute primogeniture]]}}\n{{legend|#A05050|[[Primogeniture#Male-preference cognatic primogeniture|male-preference cognatic primogeniture]]}}]]\nBefore 28 October 2011, the [[succession order]] in the American Commonwealth realms, as well as those British overseas territories in the Americas, adhered to [[male-preference cognatic primogeniture]], by which succession passed first to an individual's sons, in order of birth, and subsequently to daughters, again in order of birth. However, with the [[Succession to the Throne Act, 2013#Challenges in Canadian courts|possible exception of Canada]], following the legislative changes giving effect to the [[Perth Agreement]], succession is by [[absolute primogeniture]] for those born after 28 October 2011, whereby the eldest child inherits the throne regardless of gender. As these states share the person of their monarch with other countries, all with legislative independence, the change was implemented only once the necessary legal processes were completed in each realm. Those possessions under the Danish and Dutch crowns already adhere to absolute primogeniture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13308 |title=Succession to the throne |accessdate=18 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Dutch Monarchy |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080822054634/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13308 |archivedate = 22 August 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,4310654,00.html Females get the nod in Denmark]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.folketinget.dk/doc.aspx?/Samling/20051/lovforslag/L1/som_vedtaget.htm |title=Suggested changes to the Succession |accessdate=25 January 2009 |publisher=Parliament of Denmark |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204063605/http://www.folketinget.dk/doc.aspx?%2FSamling%2F20051%2Flovforslag%2FL1%2Fsom_vedtaget.htm |archive-date=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead }} (In Danish)</ref>\n\n==Former monarchies==\n[[File:Monumento de Cuauhtemoc.jpg|thumb|left|The monument to [[Cuauht\u00e9moc]], the last sovereign king of the [[Aztec]] Empire]]\nMost [[List of pre-Columbian cultures|pre-Columbian cultures]] of the Americas developed and flourished for centuries under monarchical systems of government. By the time [[European colonization of the Americas|Europeans arrived on the continents]] in the late 15th and early 16th centuries, however, many of these civilizations had ceased to function, due to various natural and artificial causes. Those that remained up to that period were eventually defeated by the agents of European monarchical powers, who, while they remained on the European continent, thereafter established new American administrations overseen by delegated [[viceroy]]s. Some of these colonies were, in turn, replaced by either republican states or locally founded monarchies, ultimately overtaking the entire American holdings of some European monarchs; those crowns that once held or claim territory in the Americas include the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish]], [[List of Portuguese monarchs|Portuguese]], [[List of French monarchs|French]], [[Monarchy of Sweden|Swedish]], and [[List of Russian rulers|Russian]], and even [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Baltic Courland]], [[Holy Roman Emperors|Holy Roman]], [[List of rulers of Prussia|Prussian]] and [[List of Norwegian monarchs|Norwegian]]. Certain of the locally established monarchies were themselves also overthrown through [[revolution]], leaving five current [[Pretender#Americas|pretenders to American thrones]].\n\n===Endemic monarchies===\n====Araucania and Patagonia====\n{{Main|Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia}}\n[[File:Or\u00e9lie Antoine de Tounens.JPG|thumb|right|150px|King [[Or\u00e9lie-Antoine de Tounens|Or\u00e9lie-Antoine I]] of Araucania and Patagonia]]\nThe [[Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia]] was a short-lived attempt at establishing a constitutional monarchy, founded by [[France|French]] lawyer and adventurer [[Orelie-Antoine de Tounens]] in 1860. Nominally, the \"kingdom\" encompassed the present-day  [[Argentina|Argentine]] part of [[Patagonia]] and a small segment of [[Chile]], where [[Mapuche]] peoples were fighting to maintain their sovereignty against the advancing Chilean and Argentine armed forces.<ref name=HistKing>{{cite web| url=http://www.araucania.org/araucania/aukin1_fichiers/aukin1eng.htm| title=Histoiry of the King Orllie-Antoine| publisher=Kingdom of Araucania & Patagonia| accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>  However, Or\u00e9lie-Antoine never exercised sovereignty over the claimed territory, and his ''de facto'' control was limited to nearly fourteen months and to a small territory around a town called [[Perquenco]] (at the time mainly a Mapuche tent village), which was also the declared capital of his ''kingdom''.\n\nOr\u00e9lie-Antoine felt that the indigenous peoples would be better served in negotiations with the surrounding powers by a European leader,<ref name=HistKing /> and was accordingly elected by a group of Mapuche ''loncos'' (chieftains) to be their king.<ref name=kingdom>{{cite web| url=http://www.araucania.org/| author=Marhique, Huichacurha| title=The Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia| publisher=Kingdom of Araucania & Patagonia| accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> He made efforts to gain [[Diplomatic recognition|international recognition]], and attempted to involve the French government in his project, but these efforts proved unsuccessful: the French consul concluded that Tounens was insane, and Araucania and Patagonia was never recognized by any country. The Chileans primarily ignored Or\u00e9lie-Antoine and his kingdom, at least initially, and simply went on with the [[occupation of the Araucan\u00eda]], a historical process which concluded in 1883 with Chile establishing control over the region. In the process, Or\u00e9lie-Antoine was captured in 1862, and imprisoned in an insane asylum in Chile. After several fruitless attempts to return to his kingdom (thwarted by Chilean and Argentine authorities), Tounens died penniless in 1878 in [[Tourtoirac]], France. A recent pretender, [[Jean-Michel Parasiliti di Para|Prince Antoine IV]], lived in France until 2017. The previous pretender renounced his claims to the Patagonian throne,<ref>{{cite book| last=Men\u00e9ndez| first=Braun| title=Peque\u00f1a historia patag\u00f3nica| publisher=Emec\u00e9 Editores| year=1959| page=128|language=Spanish}}</ref> even though a few Mapuches continue to recognise the Araucanian monarchy.<ref name=kingdom />\n\n====Aztec====\n{{Main|Aztec Empire}}\nThe [[Aztec]] [[Empire]] existed in the central [[Mexico|Mexican]] region between c. 1325 and 1521, and was formed by [[Aztec Triple Alliance|the triple alliance]] of the ''[[Tlatoani|tlatoque]]'' (the [[Nahuatl]] term for \"speaker\", also translated in [[English language|English]] as \"king\") of three [[city-state]]s: [[Tlacopan]], [[Texcoco (altepetl)|Texcoco]], and the capital of the empire, [[Tenochtitlan]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Concise History of Mexico |last=Hamnett |first=Brian R. |publisher=Cambridge University Press |url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn/page/51 51] |quote=Aztec Triple Alliance. |accessdate=2 January 2009|isbn=978-0-521-58916-1 |year=1999 }}</ref> While the lineage of Tenochtitlan's kings continued after [[Fall of Tenochtitlan|the city's fall to the Spanish]] on 13 August 1521, they reigned as [[Puppet state|puppet rulers]] of the [[Monarchy of Spain|King of Spain]] until the death of the last dynastic ''tlatoani'', [[Luis de Santa Mar\u00eda Nanacacipactzin]], on 27 December 1565.<ref>{{cite book |title=Codex Chimalpahin |last=de San Ant\u00f3n Mu\u00f1\u00f3n Chimalpahin Cuauhtlehuanitzin |first=Domingo Francisco |author2=Arthur J. O. Anderson |author3=Susan Schroeder |author4=Wayne Ruwet  |year=1997 |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |isbn=978-0-8061-2950-1 |page=43 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RSNdzTEHU_sC&pg=PA43&dq=Luis+de+Santa+Mar%C3%ADa+Nanacacipactzin}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\n{{Main|Empire of Brazil|United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves}}\n[[File:Maria I, Vieira.jpg|thumb|left|190px|[[Maria I of Portugal]] became the first [[list of monarchs of Brazil|Queen of Brazil]] in 1815 with the creation of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]].]]\n[[File:Pedro Am\u00e9rico - D. Pedro II na abertura da Assembl\u00e9ia Geral.jpg|180px|thumb|right|Emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil]]]]\nBrazil was created as a kingdom on 16 December 1815, when [[John VI of Portugal|Prince Jo\u00e3o]], [[Princes of Brazil|Prince of Brazil]], who was then acting as [[regent]] for his ailing mother, [[Maria I of Portugal|Queen Maria]], elevated the colony to a [[Constituent state|constituent country]] of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Vianna | first = H\u00e9lio | title = Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil: per\u00edodo colonial, monarquia e rep\u00fablica | publisher = Melhoramentos | year = 1994 | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | isbn = |language=Spanish}}</ref> While the royal court was still based in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Jo\u00e3o ascended as king of the united kingdom the following year, and returned to Portugal in 1821,<ref name=Pedro1>{{cite web| url=http://historicaltextarchive.com/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=427| author=Miller, James| title=Pedro II, Emperor of Brazil| publisher=Historical Text Archive| accessdate=17 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222184450/http://historicaltextarchive.com/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=427| archive-date=22 February 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref> leaving his son, [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]], Prince Royal, as his regent in the [[Kingdom of Brazil]]. In September of that same year, the Portuguese parliament threatened to diminish Brazil back to the status of a colony, dismantle all the royal agencies in Rio de Janeiro, and demanded Pedro return to [[Lisbon]].<ref name=Pedro1 /> The Prince, however, feared these moves would trigger separatist movements and refused to comply; instead, at the urging of his father, he [[Brazilian Declaration of Independence|declared Brazil an independent Nation]] on 7 September 1822, leading to the formation of the [[Empire of Brazil]], a constitutional monarchy. \n\nPrince Pedro became the first Emperor of Brazil on 12 October 1822, with the title of Pedro I (on that date, he was formally offered the Throne of the newly created Empire, accepted it, and was acclaimed as monarch), and his coronation took place on 1 December 1822.<ref>{{cite book| last=Vainfas| first=Ronaldo| title=Dicion\u00e1rio do Brasil Imperial| publisher=Objetiva| year=2002| location=Rio de Janeiro|language=Spanish}}</ref> After Pedro [[Abdication|abdicated]] the throne on 7 April 1831, the Brazilian empire saw only one additional monarch: [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro II]],<ref name=Pedro1 /> who reigned for 58 years before a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] overthrew the monarchy on 15 November 1889. There are two pretenders to the defunct Brazilian throne: [[Prince Luiz of Orl\u00e9ans-Braganza]], head of the Vassouras branch of the [[Brazilian Imperial Family]], and, according to legitimist claims, ''de jure'' Emperor of Brazil; and [[Prince Pedro Carlos of Orl\u00e9ans-Braganza]], head of the [[Petr\u00f3polis]] line of the Brazilian Imperial Family, and heir to the Brazilian throne according to royalists.<ref>{{cite newspaper| author=Handler, Bruce| date= 5 March 1989| title=Brazil to Decide on Return of Monarchy| journal=Los Angeles Times| page=34 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-03-05/news/mn-199_1_vote-set |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nThe Brazilian constitution of 1988 called for a general vote on the restoration of the monarchy, which was [[Brazilian constitutional referendum, 1993|held in 1993]]. The royalists went to the polls divided, with the press indicating there were actually two princes aspiring to the Brazilian throne (Dom Luiz de Orleans e Bragan\u00e7a and Dom Jo\u00e3o Henrique); this created some confusion among the voters.\n\n====Haiti====\n{{Main|First Empire of Haiti|Second Empire of Haiti|Kingdom of Haiti}}\nThe entire island of [[Hispaniola]] was first claimed on 5 December 1492, by [[Christopher Columbus]], for [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabella]], and the first Viceroy of the Americas was established along with a number of colonies throughout the Island. With the later discovery of Mexico and Peru many of the early settlers left for the main land, but some twelve cities and a hundred thousand souls remained, mainly in the Eastern part of the Island. Through the Treaty of Riswick in 1697, [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]] received the western third of the Island  from Spain as retribution and formalized the first French pirate settlement in existence since the mid-1600s,<ref>{{cite web| first=Richard A.| last=Haggerty| title=Haiti, A Country Study: French Settlement and Sovereignty| url=http://countrystudies.us/haiti/7.htm| publisher=US Library of Congress| year=1989| accessdate=30 March 2008}}</ref> with the colony administered by [[Gouverneur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|a governor-general representing the French crown]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?BioId=35359| title=Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online > Emmanuel-Auguste de Cahideuc, Comte Dubois de la Motte| publisher=University of Toronto/Universit\u00e9 Laval |accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> an arrangement that stood until the [[French Revolution]] toppled the monarchy of France on 21 September 1792. Though the French government retained control over the region of [[Saint-Domingue]], on 22 September 1804, [[Jean-Jacques Dessalines]], who had served as Governor-General of Saint-Domingue since 30 November 1803, declared himself as head of an independent [[Empire of Haiti (1804\u20131806)|Empire of Haiti]], with his coronation as Emperor Jacques I taking place on 6 October that year. After his assassination on 17 October 1806, the country was split in half, the northern portion eventually becoming the [[Kingdom of Haiti]] on 28 March 1811, with [[Henri Christophe]] installed as King Henri I.<ref name=ceac>{{cite book| last=Cheesman| first=Clive| title=The Armorial of Haiti| publisher=The College of Arms| year=2007| location=London| url=http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/| isbn=978-0-9506980-2-1| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> When King Henri committed suicide on 8 October 1820, and his son, [[Jacques-Victor Henry, Prince Royal of Haiti]], was murdered by revolutionaries ten days later, the kingdom was merged into the southern Republic of Haiti, of which [[Faustin I of Haiti|Faustin-\u00c9lie Soulouque]] was elected [[President of Haiti|president]] on 2 March 1847. Two years later, on 26 August 1849, the [[National Assembly of Haiti|Haitian national assembly]] declared the president as Emperor Faustin I, thereby re-establishing the Empire of Haiti. But this monarchical reincarnation was to be short lived as well, as a revolution broke out in the empire in 1858, resulting in Faustin abdicating the throne on 18 January 1859.<ref>{{cite book| first=Jan| last=Rogozinski| year=1999| title=A Brief History of the Caribbean| edition=Revised| publisher=Facts on File, Inc.| location=New York| page=[https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofca00rogo_0/page/220 220]| isbn=0-8160-3811-2| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofca00rogo_0/page/220}}</ref>\n\n====Inca====\n{{Main|Inca Empire}}\n[[File:TupacamaruI.JPG|thumb|160px|right|[[T\u00fapac Amaru]], the last ''Sapa Inca'' of the [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]]]]\nThe [[Inca Empire]] spread across the north western parts of South America between 1438 and 1533, ruled over by a monarch addressed as the [[Sapa Inca|''Sapa Inca'', ''Sapa'', or ''Apu'']]. The [[Inca civilization]] emerged in the [[Kingdom of Cusco]], and expanded to become the ''Ttahuantin-suyu'', or \"land of the four sections\", each ruled by a governor or viceroy called ''Apu-cuna'', under the leadership of the central ''Sapa Inca''. The Inca Empire eventually fell to the Spanish in 1533, when the last ''Sapa Inca'' of the empire, [[Atahualpa]], was captured and executed on 29 August.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761560004_3/Inca_Empire.html#s12 |title=Inca Empire: Spanish Conquest |accessdate=2 January 2009 |publisher=MSN Encarta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kyWmnijq?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761560004_3/Inca_Empire.html|archivedate=2 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The conquerors installed other ''Sapa Inca'' beginning with Atahualpa's brother, [[T\u00fapac Huallpa]]. [[Manco Inca Yupanqui]], originally also a puppet Inca Emperor installed by the Spaniards, rebelled and founded the small independent [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]], and the line continued until the death of [[T\u00fapac Amaru]] in 1572.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761593238/amar%C3%BA_tupac.html |title=T\u00fapac Amaru |accessdate=19 January 2009 |publisher=MSN Encarta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kx7Qgcer?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761593238/amar%C3%BA_tupac.html|archivedate=1 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Maya====\n{{Main|Maya Civilization}}\nThe [[Maya civilization]] was located on the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] and into the [[Isthmus|isthmian]] portion of North America, and the northern portion of [[Central America]] (Guatemala, Belize, El Salvador and Honduras) was formed of a number of ''ajawil'', ''ajawlel'', or ''ajawlil''\u2013 hierarchical polities headed by an hereditary ruler known as a ''[[Ajaw|kuhul ajaw]]'' (the [[Mayan languages|Mayan]] term indicating a sovereign leader).{{#tag:ref|Both terms appear in early Colonial texts (including ''Papeles de Paxbol\u00f3n'') where they are used as synonymous to Aztec and Spanish terms for supreme rulers and their domains \u2013 ''tlahtoani'' (''[[Tlatoani]]'') and ''tlahtocayotl'', ''rey'', or ''magestad'' and ''reino'', ''se\u00f1or'' and ''se\u00f1or\u00edo'', or ''dominio''.|group=N|name=Maya1}} Despite constant warfare and shifts in regional power, most [[Maya civilization#Political structures|Maya kingdoms]] remained a part of the region's landscape, even following subordination to hegemonic rulers through conquest or dynastic union. Nonetheless, the Maya civilization began its decline in the 8th and 9th centuries, and by the time of the arrival of the Spanish, only a few kingdoms remained, such as the [[Peten Itza kingdom]], [[Mam people|Mam]], [[Kaqchikel people|Kaqchikel]], and the [[K'iche' Kingdom of Q'umarkaj]]. On 13 March 1697, the last [[Itza]] Maya king was [[Spanish conquest of Pet\u00e9n#Fall of Nojpet\u00e9n|defeated at Nojpet\u00e9n]] by the forces of King [[Philip IV of Spain]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Ancient Maya |last=Sharer |first=Robert J. |author2=Sylvanus Griswold Morley |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-2130-1 |page=423 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=c65_g571LyAC&pg=PA423&lpg=PA423&dq=1697+Tayasal |year=1994 }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n{{Main|First Mexican Empire|Second Mexican Empire}}\nWith the victory of the [[Mexico|Mexicans]] over the Spanish imperial army in 1821, the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain]] came to a conclusion. The newly independent [[Congress of Mexico|Mexican Congress]] still desired that [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|King Ferdinand VII]], or another member of the [[House of Bourbon]], agree to be installed as Emperor of Mexico, thereby forming a type of [[personal union]] with Spain. The Spanish monarchy, however, refused to recognise the new state, and decreed that it would allow no other European prince to take the throne of Mexico. Thus, the Mexican [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide]] was crowned as Augustine I on 19 May 1822, with an official decree of confirmation issued two days following. Only a few months later, Augustine dissolved a factious congress, thereby prompting an enraged [[Antonio L\u00f3pez de Santa Anna]] to mount a coup, which led to the declaration of a republic on 1 December 1822. In order to end the unrest, Augustine abdicated on 19 March 1823 and left the country, and the Mexican monarchy was abolished. After hearing that the situation in Mexico had only grown worse since his abdication, Iturbide returned from England on 11 May 1824, but was detained upon setting foot in Mexico and, without trial, was executed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/379167/Mexico/27357/The-Mexican-Empire-1821-23 |title=History \u00bb Independence \u00bb The Mexican Empire, 1821\u201323 |accessdate=2 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date=}}</ref>\n[[File:X-Large Portrait of Maximiliano.jpg|170px|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I of Mexico]], by [[Franz Xaver Winterhalter]]]]\n\n[[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], elected as [[President of Mexico]] on 19 January 1858, suspended all repayments on Mexico's foreign debts (save those owed to the [[United States]]), leading France, the United Kingdom, and Spain to send a joint expeditionary force that took [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz]] in December 1861. Ju\u00e1rez then repaid the debts, after which British and Spanish troops withdrew, but Emperor [[Napoleon III of France]] used the situation as a pretext to overthrow the republic and install a monarch friendly to the interests of France. Archduke Maximilian, brother of the [[Emperor of Austria]], was elevated as [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico]], thereby re-establishing the Mexican monarchy, but the new emperor ultimately did not bow to Napoleon's wishes, leading the latter to withdraw the majority of his influence from Mexico. Regardless, Maximilian was still viewed as a French puppet, and an illegitimate leader of the country. As well, at the end of the [[American Civil War]], US troops moved to the Mexico-US border as part of a planned invasion, seeing the establishment of the Second Mexican Empire as an infringement on their [[Monroe Doctrine]]. Backed by the Americans, ex-president Ju\u00e1rez mobilised to retake power, and defeated Maximilian at [[Quer\u00e9taro, Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]] on 15 May 1867. The Emperor was arraigned before a military tribunal, sentenced to death, and executed at the ''Cerro de las Campanas'' on 19 June 1867.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/379167/Mexico/27361/French-intervention |title=History \u00bb Independence \u00bb French intervention |accessdate=2 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date=}}</ref>\n\n====Miskito====\nThe [[Miskito people|Miskito]] people of Central America were governed by the authority of a monarch, but one who shared his royal powers with a governor and a general. The origins of the monarchy are unknown; however, its sovereignty was lost when King Edward I of the Miskito Nation signed the [[Treaty of Friendship and Alliance]] with King [[George II of the United Kingdom]], putting the Miskito kingdom under the [[British protectorate|British protection]] and law. At the cessation of the [[American Revolutionary War]], King [[George III of the United Kingdom]], via the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]], relinquished control of the Miskito's lands, though Britain continued an unofficial protectorate over the kingdom to protect Miskito interests against Spanish encroachments. After British interest in the region waned, [[Nicaragua]] dissolved and occupied the Miskito kingdom in 1894,<ref>{{cite news| first=Rory| last=Carroll| title=Nicaragua's green lobby is leaving rainforest people 'utterly destitute'| date=26 November 2006| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2006/nov/26/famine.conservation| work=Guardian Unlimited|accessdate=7 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref> with the monarch thereafter becoming known as the Hereditary Chief. [[Norton Cuthbert Clarence]] is the current pretender to the Miskito Kingdom and Hereditary Chief of the Miskito Nation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Penny Ante Imperialism: The Mosquito Shore and the Bay of Honduras |last=Naylor |first=Robert A.  |publisher= University of Virginia |isbn=978-0-8386-3323-6 |page=310 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eJ8WAAAAYAAJ |year=1989 }}</ref>\n\n====Ta\u00edno====\nThe [[Ta\u00edno people|Ta\u00edno]]s were an indigenous civilization spread across those islands today lying within the [[Bahamas]], [[Greater Antilles]], and the northern [[Lesser Antilles]]. These regions were divided into kingdoms (the island of [[Hispaniola]] alone was segmented into five kingdoms), which were themselves sometimes sub-divided into provinces. Each kingdom was led by a ''[[cacique]]'', or \"chieftain\", who was advised in his exercise of royal power by a council of priests/healers known as ''bohiques''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html| title=Caciques, nobles and their regalia| accessdate=9 November 2006| publisher=elmuseo.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061009090513/http://elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html |archivedate = 9 October 2006}}</ref> The line of succession, however, was [[matrilineal]], whereby if there was no male heir to become ''cacigue'', the title would pass to the eldest child, whether son or daughter, of the deceased's sister.<ref name=Rouse>{{cite book| last=Rouse| first=Irving| title=The Tainos: Rise and Decline of the people who greeted Columbus| url=https://archive.org/details/tainosrisedeclin00rous| url-access=registration| year=1992| publisher=Yale University Press| location=New York| isbn=0-300-05696-6}}</ref> After battling for centuries with the [[Island Caribs|Carib]], the Ta\u00edno empire finally succumbed to disease and genocide brought by the Spanish colonisers.<ref>{{cite book| last=Sale| first=Kirkpatrick| title=The Conquest of Paradise| page=157| isbn=0-333-57479-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/580786/Taino| title=Ta\u00edno people| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica| accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Colonial monarchies===\n====Courland====\n[[File:Jacob Kettler.gif|170px|thumb|right|Jacob Kettler, Duke of Courland and Semigallia tried to established a colony in the Americas.]]\n{{main|Duchy of Courland and Semigallia}}\nAfter a number of failed attempts at colonising [[Tobago]], Duke [[Jacob Kettler]] of [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Courland and Semigallia]] sent one more ship to the island, which landed there on 20 May 1654, carrying soldiers and colonists, who named the island ''[[Courland colonization of the Americas|New Courland]]''. At approximately the same time, Dutch colonies were established at other locations on the island, and eventually outgrew those of the Duchy of Courland in population. When the Duke was captured by Swedish forces in 1658, Dutch settlers overtook the Courland colonies, forcing the Governor to surrender. After a return of the territory to Courland through the 1660 [[Treaty of Oliwa]], a number of attempts were made by the next Duke of Courland (Friedrich Casimir Kettler) at re-colonisation, but these met with failure, and he sold New Courland in 1689.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.colonialvoyage.com/tobago.html| title=Dutch Portuguese Colonial History > Dutch and Courlanders in Tobago| publisher=Colonialvoyage.com| accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====France====\nAfter [[Francis I of France|King Francis I]] commissioned [[Jacques Cartier]] to search out an eastern route to [[Asia]], the city of [[Port Royal, Annapolis County, Nova Scotia|Port Royal]] was founded on 27 July 1605 in what is today [[Nova Scotia]]. From there, the French Crown's empire in the Americas grew to include areas of land surrounding the [[Great Lakes]] and down the [[Mississippi River]], as well as islands in the Caribbean, and the [[French Guiana|north eastern shore of South America]]; the [[New France|Viceroyalty of New France]] was eventually made into a royal province of France in 1663 by [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]].<ref>{{cite journal| last=Emerson| first=Rupert| title=Colonialism and Decolonization| journal=Journal of Contemporary History| volume=4| issue=1| pages=3\u201316| date=January 1969| doi=10.1177/002200946900400101}}</ref> Some regions were lost to the Spanish or British Crowns through conflict and treaties, and those that were still possessions of the French king on 21 December 1792 came under republican rule when the French monarchy was abolished on that day.<ref>{{Cite book| first=Christopher| last=Hibbert| title=The Days of the French Revolution| year=1980| location=New York| publisher=Quill, William Morrow| url=https://books.google.com/?id=yr1z38HCkdAC&dq=Hibbert+French+Revolution| isbn=0-688-03704-6| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| first=Georges| last=Lefebvre| title=The French Revolution: From Its Origins to 1793| year=1971| publisher=Columbia University Press| url=https://books.google.com/?id=I2oA5MtB0ZkC&dq=Lefebvre+estates+general| isbn=0-231-08598-2| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref>\nUpon several restorations of the monarchy, the royal presence in the Americas ended with the collapse of the [[Second French Empire]] under [[Napoleon III]] in 1870.\n\n====Holy Roman Empire of German Nationalities====\n{{main|Holy Roman Empire}}\n[[File:Quaterionenadler David de Negker.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.15|Double-headed eagle with coats of arms of individual states, the symbol of the Holy Roman Empire (painting from 1510)]]\nMost important of Holy Roman Emperors Clan later named after [[Habsburg Castle|Habsburg]] in Swiss Aargau descends from [[Africa]], and its first named [[ancestor]] is [[Heracles]]. The period in which [[Habsburg|Habsburg Dynasty]] has been ruling [[Spanish Habsburg|Spain]], [[Spanish Netherlands|The Netherlands]], [[History of Germany|Germany]], [[History of Austria|Austria]] and other Central European Regions from the [[Renaissance]] on is named [[Spanish Golden Age|The Golden Age]]. This period of [[Conquistador|Conquistatores]] after [[Catholicos|Rey Catolicos]] who fought in [[Reconquista]] against [[Al-Andalus|Spanish Islam]] and [[Sephardi Jews|Sephards]], who moved back to [[Maghreb|Africa]], The Spanish Netherlands or to the exceptional tolerant [[Ottoman Empire]] of its time. The [[Kingdom of Spain]] underwent enormous economic growth by virtue of its colonies in [[Americas|South America]]. [[Cadiz]] city of the [[Phoenicians]] also named oldest of the European towns and later the place to start [[C\u00e1diz (Parliament of Andalusia constituency)|Spanish Parlament]] and [[Seville]] were the most priviliged cities, because of their location in the [[Iberian Peninsula|Western Iberian Peninsula]]. Monuments like [[Christopher Columbus|Cristoforo Colombo Epitaph]] and Seville Cathedral with its famous Giralda of [[Abu Yusuf Yaqub al-Mansur]] can be seen as a sign for [[Rinascimento]] still today and in the future. [[Prussia|Prussian Colonies]] of the 18 century were f.e. Fredericksburg in Ghana and some other small settlements of Austrian Marie-Therese Habsburg in Africa but also in [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands|South Asia]]. Therefore Trade and Knowledge Exchange always existed between [[Americas]] and the Roman Empire of German Nation, especially under der Rule of [[Karl V|Charles V]] [[Plus Ultra]] by help of Merchantise families as [[Welser]] and the [[Fugger]] of Augsburg and Nurnberg in [[Bavaria]] in South Germany. As Hightech can be seen [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]] Arts, [[Johannes Gutenberg|Printing Press Progress]] and spread of [[Lutheranism|Luterhan Church]], not only in Europe but also within the [[Indians]] in the Americas and Global. People of all professional backgrounds were migrating to find their new luck to fulfil their dreams not only in the past but, remember spread of [[food culture]], still today. [[Coat of arms of Spain|Spanish Coat of Arms]] still expresses the curiosity of a continent around 1500.\nEnd of Europeans Wealth Unity can be seen in the Siege of [[Elizabeth I of England]] against the [[Armada]] in the Atlantic and perhaps a slowdown of Continental Europe Power against United Kingdom and its [[Commonwealth]]. After [[Bourbon Spain|Bourbon Emperor]] gained Spanish Crown by [[Duke of marlborough|Duke of Marlboroughs]] Siege against glorious [[Prince Eugene of Savoy|Eugene of Savoia]], Habsburgs most important warhero, Central Europe only was assumed to get back trading power by construction of [[Suez Canal|Canal of Suez]]. But also migration from central Europe to [[Russia]] and Asia, which was most famously reached by [[Hanse]] on [[Baltic Sea]] and on the way to [[Black Sea]] and beyond. Therefore see rich and diverse Russian History reflected also in many German expressions still in the Russian language. In between Germans were always many other European Nations as [[Jewish People|Jewish Populations]], [[Romani People]] and important for Arts the [[Italian artists]] moving all over the world to spread adequate styles for [[Noblepeople|Nobles]], not to forget [[Music baroque|Musicians]]. Austrias last colony was [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Mexico of Maximilian]] and Germany had to leave Africa and Oceania after [[World War I|WorldWarI]] and its tragic loose of powers. Because these disasters ended in another even more cruel war and unique [[Cold War]] which gained their Happy End in Summer 1989 by [[Fall of the Wall]]. So not only shadow of [[Karl Habsburg|Karl I Habsburg]] losing Austrian Habsburg Empire and his death in Madeira, but more Ottomans losing power in one of the oldest multinational Empires of the world can still to be recognised in todays conflicts globally. Following [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilians I]] theme ''Tu Felix Austria Nube..'' some of the glorious family were happily married in Brazil too. Therefore not only because of [[Latin Church]] and some islands of luck in where local identity could resist Technical Progress and newer influences a strong [[Feelgood|feelgood]] connection may be assumed.\n\n\n[[File:Alexander II of Russia by K.Makovskiy (1881, GTG).jpg|170px|thumb|left|[[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]], Emperor of Russia, who sold Alaska to the United States of America in 1867]]\n\n====Russia====\n{{main|Russian Empire}}\nThe first permanent Russian settlements in what is today the US state of [[Alaska]] were set down in the 1790s, forming [[Russian Alaska]], after [[Russian Czar|Tsar]] [[Peter I of Russia|Peter I]] called for expeditions across the [[Bering Strait]] in 1725,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://kodiakisland.net/timeline.html| title=Alaska History Timeline| publisher=Kodiak Island Internet Directory| accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> with the region administered by the head of the [[Russian-American Company]] as the Emperor's representative. Another Russian outpost, [[Fort Ross, California|Fort Ross]], was established in 1812 in what is now [[California]].<ref>{{cite book| last=Nordlander| first=David J.| title=For God & Tsar: A Brief History of Russian America 1741\u20131867| publisher=Alaska Natural History Association| location=Anchorage| year=1994| isbn=0-930931-15-7}}</ref> The colonies, however, were never profitable enough to maintain Russian interest in the area, with the population only ever reaching a maximum of 700. Fort Ross was sold in 1841, and in 1867, a deal was brokered whereby [[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]] sold his Alaskan territory to the United States of America for $7,200,000, and the official transfer took place on 30 October that year.<ref>{{cite book| last=Farrar| first=Victor John| title=The Annexation of Russian America to the United States| publisher=Russell & Russell| location=New York| year=1966}}</ref>\n\n====Portugal====\n[[File:Maria I, Vieira.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Queen [[Maria I of Portugal]], first [[Kingdom of Brazil|Queen of Brazil]] and the only European monarch to have been born in the Americas.]]\n{{main|Portuguese Empire}}\nThe United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves came into being in the wake of Portugal's war with [[Napoleonic France]]. The Portuguese Prince Regent, the future King John VI, with his incapacitated mother, Queen [[Maria I of Portugal]] and the Royal Court, [[Transfer of the Portuguese Court to Brazil|escaped]] to the [[colony of Brazil]] in 1808.\nWith the defeat of Napoleon in 1815, there were calls for the return of the Portuguese Monarch to Lisbon; the Portuguese Prince Regent enjoyed life in Rio de Janeiro, where the monarchy was at the time more popular and where he enjoyed more freedom, and he was thus unwilling to return to Europe. However, those advocating the return of the Court to Lisbon argued that Brazil was only a colony and that it was not right for Portugal to be governed from a colony. On the other hand, leading Brazilian courtiers pressed for the elevation of Brazil from the rank of a colony, so that they could enjoy the full status of being nationals of the mother-country. Brazilian nationalists also supported the move, because it indicated that Brazil would no longer be submissive to the interests of Portugal, but would be of equal status within a transatlantic monarchy.\n\n====Spain====\n{{main|Monarchy of Spain}}\nBeginning in 1492 with the voyages of [[Christopher Columbus]] under the direction of [[Isabella I of Castile]], the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish Crown]] amassed a large [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|American empire]] over three centuries, spreading first from the [[Caribbean]] to [[Central America]], most of [[South America]], [[Mexico]], what is today the [[Southwestern United States]], and the Pacific coast of [[North America]] up to [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartroli |first=Tom\u00e1s |title=Presencia hisp\u00e1nica en la costa noroeste de Am\u00e9rica |publisher=Universidad de British Columbio |location=Vancouver |year=1968|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first=Angelina |last=Mir\u00f3 |title=Catalans a la costa oest del Canad\u00e0: Els catalans a la Col\u00fambia Brit\u00e0nica al s.XVIII |url=http://www.histocat.cat/pdf/catalans_al_canada.pdf |accessdate=19 December 2008 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030000815/http://www.histocat.cat/pdf/catalans_al_canada.pdf |archivedate=30 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> These regions formed the majority of the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain]], the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]], the [[Viceroyalty of New Granada]], and the [[Viceroyalty of the R\u00edo de la Plata]] in each of which the Spanish monarch was represented by [[List of viceroys of New Spain|a viceroy]]. By the early 19th century, however, the Spanish sovereign's possessions in the Americas began a series of independence movements, which culminated in the Crown's loss of all its colonies on the mainland of North and South America by 1825. The remaining colonies of [[Cuba]] and [[Puerto Rico]] were occupied by the [[United States]] following the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], ending Spanish rule in the Americas by 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=Mexico and the United States |last=Lee |first=Stacey |publisher=Marshall Cavendish |isbn=978-0-7614-7402-9 |page=777 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSzyMGh8pNwC&pg=PA777&dq=spanish+empire+in+1899+spanish+american |date=October 2002}}</ref>\n\n====Sweden====\n{{main|Monarchy of Sweden}}\nFor a period of time the French ceded sovereignty of the island of [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] to the Swedes but it was eventually returned. Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (1784\u20131878) was operated as a porto Franco (free port). The capital city of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] retains its Swedish name.\n\n===Self-proclaimed monarchies===\n[[File:James Strang daguerreotype (1856).jpg|thumb|125px|1856 [[daguerreotype]] of James Strang]]\nThese entities were never recognized ''de jure'' as legitimate governments, but still sometimes exercised a certain degree of local control or influence within their respective locations until the death of their \"monarch\":\n\n;James J. Strang\n[[James Strang]], a would-be successor to the [[Latter Day Saints|Mormon]] prophet [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]], proclaimed himself \"king\" over his [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)|church]] in 1850, which was then concentrated mostly on [[Beaver Island (Lake Michigan)|Beaver Island]] in [[Lake Michigan]].  On 8 July of that year, he was physically crowned in an elaborate coronation ceremony complete with crown, sceptre, throne, ermine robe and breastplate.<ref>Weeks, Robert P. \"For His Was the Kingdom, and the Power, and the Glory...Briefly\" ''American Heritage'' 21 (4).  The sceptre is preserved in the vault of the archives of the [[Community of Christ]] church in Independence, Missouri; the whereabouts of Strang's remaining regalia is a mystery.</ref>  Although he never claimed legal sovereignty over Beaver Island or any other geographical entity, Strang managed (as a member of the [[Michigan State Legislature]]) to have his \"kingdom\" constituted as a separate [[Manitou County, Michigan|county]], where his followers held all county offices, and Strang's word was law.  U.S. President [[Millard Fillmore]] ordered an investigation into Strang's colony, which resulted in Strang's trial in [[Detroit]] for [[treason]], trespass, [[counterfeiting]] and other crimes, but the jury found the \"king\" innocent of all charges.  Strang was eventually assassinated by two disgruntled followers in 1856, and his kingdom&mdash;together with his royal regalia&mdash;vanished.\n\n;Joshua Norton\n[[Emperor Norton|Joshua Abraham Norton]], an Englishman who emigrated to [[San Francisco]], [[California]] in 1849, proclaimed himself \"Emperor of These United States\" in 1859, later adding the title \"Protector of Mexico\".  Though never recognized by the U.S. or Mexican governments, he was accorded a certain degree of deference within San Francisco itself, including reserved balcony seats (for which he was never charged) at local theatres, and salutes by policemen who passed him on the street.  Specially printed currency authorized by Norton was accepted as [[legal tender]] within several businesses in the city.  When Norton died in 1880, he was given a lavish funeral attended by over 30,000 persons.<ref>[http://www.emperornorton.net/NortonI-Cowan.html Norton I, Emperor of the United States and Protector of Mexico]</ref>\n\n;James Harden-Hickey\n[[James Harden-Hickey]] was a self-proclaimed prince, who attempted to establish the so-called [[Principality of Trinidad]] on [[Trindade Island|Trindade]] and the [[Martim Vaz Islands]] in the South Atlantic Ocean during the late 19th century. Although initially garnering some newspaper attention, Hickey's claims were ignored or ridiculed by other nations, and the islands eventually were occupied by military forces from nearby Brazil which remain there to the present day.\n\n;Matthew Dowdy Shiell\nA self-proclaimed monarch of the so-called [[Kingdom of Redonda]], an island in the [[Caribbean Sea]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}  Whether Shiell ever actually claimed to be king of this tiny islet is open to debate; however, other individuals later claimed the title of \"King of Redonda,\" without having apparently ever tried to physically establish themselves on the island itself.{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Afro-Bolivian monarchy]]\n* [[Canadian Confederation]]\n* [[List of monarchs in the Americas]]\n* [[List of the last monarchs in the Americas]]\n* [[Monarchies in Africa]]\n* [[Monarchies in Europe]]\n* [[Monarchies in Oceania]]\n* [[Monarchism]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | author=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] | date=11 July 2006 | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/index.html | title=CIA \u2014 The World Factbook | work=[[The World Factbook]] | accessdate=25 November 2008 }}\n* {{cite web | author=Central Intelligence Agency | date=18 July 2006 | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/world-leaders-1/index.html | title=World Leaders | work=[[World Leaders]] | accessdate=25 November 2008 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{American monarchies}}\n{{Monarchies}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monarchies In The Americas}}\n[[Category:Americas]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of North America| ]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of South America| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the former Kingdom of Hawaii and other Pacific Ocean monarchies|Monarchies in Oceania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:Monarchies of America2.png|thumb|right|{{legend|#A51645|American [[monarchy|monarchies]]}}\n{{legend|#ff6ea7|Non-American monarchies}}{{legend|#967bff|Former monarchies with [[pretender]]s}}]]\n[[File:Crown of Saint Edward (Heraldry).svg|thumb|right|[[St. Edward's Crown]], a part of the [[British Crown Jewels]], is used in the heraldry of those American states with Queen [[Elizabeth II]] as sovereign.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/fr-rf/drap-pers-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion > The Canadian Monarchy > The Queen's Personal Canadian Flag| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| authorlink=Royal Household#The Royal Household of the United Kingdom| journal=Royal Insight Magazine| title=Mailbox| issue=September 2006| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| location=London| url=http://www.royalinsight.gov.uk/output/Page5467.asp| accessdate=1 December 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119134240/http://www.royalinsight.gov.uk/output/Page5467.asp| archivedate=19 November 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\n\nThere are 13 '''monarchies in the Americas''' ([[Self-governance|self-governing]] states and territories that have a [[monarch]] as [[head of state]]). Each is a [[constitutional monarchy]], wherein the sovereign inherits his or her office, usually keeping it until death or [[abdication]], and is bound by laws and customs in the exercise of their powers. Ten of these monarchies are independent states; they equally share Queen [[Elizabeth II]], who resides primarily in the [[United Kingdom]], as their respective sovereign, making them part of a global group known as the [[Commonwealth realm]]s. The others are [[dependent territory|dependencies]] of three European monarchies. As such, none of the monarchies in the [[Americas]] have a permanently residing monarch.\n\nThese crowns continue a history of monarchy in the Americas that reaches back to before [[European colonization of the Americas|European colonization]]. Both tribal and more complex [[pre-Columbian]] societies existed under monarchical forms of government, with some expanding to form vast [[empire]]s under a central [[Monarch|king]] figure, while others did the same with a decentralized collection of tribal regions under a hereditary [[Tribal chief|chieftain]]. None of the contemporary monarchies, however, are descended from those pre-colonial royal systems, instead either having their historical roots in, or still being a part of, the current [[Monarchies in Europe|European monarchies]] that spread their reach across the [[Atlantic Ocean]], beginning in the mid 14th century.\n\nFrom that date on, through the [[Age of Discovery]], European colonization brought extensive American territory under the control of Europe's monarchs, though the majority of these colonies subsequently gained independence from their rulers. Some did so via armed conflict with their mother countries, as in the [[American Revolution]] and the [[Latin American wars of independence]], usually severing all ties to the overseas monarchies in the process. Others gained full sovereignty by legislative paths, such as [[Canada]]'s [[patriation]] of its constitution from the [[United Kingdom]]. A certain number of former colonies became [[republic]]s immediately upon achieving self-governance. The remainder continued with [[Endemism|endemic]] constitutional monarchies\u2014in the cases of [[Haiti]], [[Mexico]], and [[Brazil]]\u2014with their own resident monarch and, for places such as Canada and some island states in the [[Caribbean]], sharing their monarch with their former [[metropole]], the most recently created being [[Monarchy of Belize|that of Belize]] in 1981.\n\n==Current monarchies==\n===American monarchies===\n{{main|Lists of monarchs in the Americas}}\nWhile the incumbent of each of the American monarchies is the same person and resides predominantly in Europe, each of the states are [[Sovereignty|sovereign]] and thus have distinct local monarchies [[Seat (legal entity)|seated]] in their respective [[Capital (political)|capital]]s, with the monarch's day-to-day governmental and ceremonial duties generally carried out by an appointed local [[viceroy]].\n\n====Antigua and Barbuda====\n{{main|Monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda}}\nThe monarchy of [[Antigua and Barbuda]] has its roots in the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish monarchy]], under the authority of which the islands were first colonized in the late 15th century, and later the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British monarchy]], as a [[Crown colony]]. On 1 November 1981, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Antigua and Barbuda|Governor-General of Antigua and Barbuda]], Sir [[Rodney Williams (governor-general)|Rodney Williams]].<ref name=FCO>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/antigua-barbuda| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Antigua and Barbuda| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119085209/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/antigua-barbuda| archive-date=19 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nElizabeth and her [[Prince consort|royal consort]], [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], included Antigua and Barbuda in their 1966 [[Caribbean]] tour, and again in [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|the Queen's Silver Jubilee]] tour of October 1977. Elizabeth returned once more in 1985.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| title=The  Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean realms| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> For the country's 25th anniversary of independence, on 30 October 2006, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], opened Antigua and Barbuda's new parliament building, reading a message from his mother, the Queen. The Duke of York visited Antigua and Barbuda in January 2001.<ref name=FCO />\n\n====The Bahamas====\n{{main|Monarchy of The Bahamas}}\nThe monarchy of [[The Bahamas]] has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonized in the late 15th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony, after 1717. On 10 July 1973, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bahamas.gov.bs/bahamasweb2/home.nsf/vContentW/AD50C97FCEE345FE06256F02007F60C0| last=Government of the Bahamas| authorlink1=Politics of the Bahamas| title=The Government of the Bahamas > About The Government > Overview and Structure of the Government| publisher=Government of the Bahamas| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of The Bahamas. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of the Bahamas|Governor-General of the Bahamas]], Sir [[Cornelius A. Smith]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bahamaspress.com/2019/06/17/the-cabinet-office-announces-the-honourable-cornelius-a-smith-to-serve-as-the-11th-governor-general-in-an-independent-bahamas/|title=The Cabinet Office announces The Honourable Cornelius A. Smith to serve as the 11th Governor-General in an Independent Bahamas! {{!}} Bahamaspress.com|last=media|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n====Barbados====\n{{main|Monarchy of Barbados}}\nThe monarchy of Barbados has its roots in the [[Monarchy of England|English monarchy]], under the authority of which the island was claimed in 1625 and first colonized in 1627,<ref name=BParlHist>{{cite web| url=http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php| last=The Clerk Of Parliament| title=The Barbados Parliament > Parliament's History| publisher=Parliament of Barbados| accessdate=1 December 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523083154/http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php| archivedate=23 May 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and later the British monarchy. By the 18th century, Barbados became one of the main seats of the British Crown's authority in the [[British West Indies]], and then, after an attempt in 1958 at [[West Indies Federation|a federation with other West Indian colonies]], continued as a [[self-governing colony]] until, on 30 November 1966, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Barbados. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Barbados|Governor-General of Barbados]], Sir [[Elliott Belgrave]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.barbados.gov.bb/gg.htm| last=Government Information Service| title=Government > Governor General| publisher=Government of Barbados| accessdate=5 January 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081118142029/http://www.barbados.gov.bb/gg.htm <!--Added by H3llBot-->| archivedate=18 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, Elizabeth's cousin, [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent]], opened the second session of the first parliament of the newly established country,<ref name=BParlHist /> before the Queen herself, along with Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, toured Barbados. Elizabeth returned for her Silver Jubilee in 1977, and again in 1989, to mark the 350th anniversary of the establishment of the Barbadian parliament.<ref name=BParlHist /><ref name=Buck1>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| title=The Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean Realms| publisher=Her Majesty\u2019s Stationery Office| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Barbados|Prime Minister]] [[Owen Arthur]] called for a referendum on Barbados becoming a republic to be held in 2005,<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas |first=Norman |title=Barbados to vote on move to republic |publisher=Caribbean News |date=7 February 2005 |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/02/07/vote.shtml |accessdate=1 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228082001/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/02/07/vote.shtml |archivedate=28 December 2007 }}</ref> though the vote was then pushed back to \"at least 2006\" in order to speed up Barbados' integration in the [[CARICOM Single Market and Economy]]. It was announced on 26 November 2007 that [[Barbadian republic referendum|the referendum]] would be held in 2008, together with the [[Barbadian general election, 2008|general election that year]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Staff| title=Referendum on Republic to be bundled with election| publisher=Caribbean Broadcasting Corporation| date=26 November 2007| url=http://www.evernetcorp.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=13417| accessdate=27 November 2007}}</ref> The vote was, however, postponed again to a later point, due to administrative concerns.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Gollop |title=Vote Off |url=http://www.nationnews.com/story/317791120649409.php |publisher=The Nation |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=22 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228045102/http://www.nationnews.com/story/317791120649409.php |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Belize====\n{{main|Monarchy of Belize}}\nBelize was, until the 15th century, a part of the [[Maya civilization|Mayan Empire]], containing smaller states headed by a hereditary ruler known as an ''[[ajaw]]'' (later ''k\u2019uhul ajaw'').{{#tag:ref|Both terms appear in early Colonial texts (including ''Papeles de Paxbol\u00f3n'') where they are used as synonymous to Aztec and Spanish terms for supreme rulers and their domains \u2013 ''tlahtoani'' (''[[Tlatoani]]'') and ''tlahtocayotl'', ''rey'', or ''magestad'' and ''reino'', ''se\u00f1or'' and ''se\u00f1or\u00edo'', or ''dominio''.|group=N|name=Maya1}} The present monarchy of Belize has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the area was first colonised in the 16th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 21 September 1981, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Belize.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.governmentofbelize.gov.bz/ab_politics.html| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421070007/http://www.governmentofbelize.gov.bz/ab_politics.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=21 April 2008| last=Government of Belize| authorlink=Politics of Belize| title=About Belize > Politics > Constitution and Government| publisher=Government of Belize| accessdate=5 January 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Belize|Governor-General of Belize]], Sir [[Colville Young]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/belize| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Belize| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222205656/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/belize/| archive-date=22 December 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\n{{main|Monarchy of Canada}}\n[[File:Mohawk-kings.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Painting of the [[Four Mohawk Kings]], done during their visit with Queen [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]] in 1710]]\n[[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canada's aboriginal peoples]] had systems of governance organised in a fashion similar to the [[Western world|Occidental]] concept of monarchy;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldandi.com/specialreport/2001/october/Sa21577.htm |last=Kehoe |first=Alice Beck |title=First Nations History |publisher=The World & I Online |date=October 2001 |accessdate=2 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610234600/http://www.worldandi.com/specialreport/2001/october/Sa21577.htm |archivedate=10 June 2011 }}</ref> European explorers often referred to hereditary leaders of tribes as kings.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pequotmuseum.org/Home/CrossPaths/CrossPathsFall2002/JohnSimonsEngravingsoftheFourKingsMoreThanMeetstheEye.htm| last=Simon| first=John| title=Engravings of the Four Kings: More Than Meets the Eye| publisher=Pequot Museum| accessdate=1 January 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121184743/http://www.pequotmuseum.org/Home/CrossPaths/CrossPathsFall2002/JohnSimonsEngravingsoftheFourKingsMoreThanMeetstheEye.htm| archivedate=21 November 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The present monarchy of Canada has its roots in the [[List of French monarchs|French]] and English monarchies, under the authority of which the area was colonised in the 16th-18th centuries, and later the British monarchy. The country became a self-governing confederation on 1 July 1867, recognised as a kingdom in its own right,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/publctn/101/102-eng.cfm |last=Department of Canadian Heritage |authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage |title=The Crown in Canada |publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada |accessdate=2 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210231140/http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/publctn/101/102-eng.cfm |archivedate=10 December 2014 }}</ref> but did not have full legislative autonomy from the British Crown until the passage of the [[Statute of Westminster 1931|Statute of Westminster]] on 11 December 1931,<ref name=COM>{{cite book| last=MacLeod| first=Kevin S.| title=A Crown of Maples: Constitutional Monarchy in Canada| publisher=Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Canada| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/fr-rf/crnCdn/crn_mpls-eng.pdf| isbn=978-0-662-46012-1| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> retaining the then reigning monarch, [[George V]], as monarch of the newly formed monarchy of Canada. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[Governor General of Canada]], [[Julie Payette]], and in each of the provinces by a [[Lieutenant-Governor (Canada)|lieutenant governor]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mun.ca/govhouse/duties.html| last=Government House| authorlink=Government House (Newfoundland and Labrador)| title=Role and duties of the Lieutenant-Governor| publisher=Memorial University| accessdate=18 January 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080223001655/http://www.mun.ca/govhouse/duties.html |archivedate = 23 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Grenada====\n{{main|Monarchy of Grenada}}\nThe monarchy of [[Grenada]] has its roots in the French monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the mid 17th century, and later the English and then British monarchy, as a Crown colony.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/grenada?profile=history&pg=3| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Grenada| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121132511/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/grenada?profile=history&pg=3| archive-date=21 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 February 1974, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Grenada. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Grenada|Governor-General of Grenada]], currently Dame [[C\u00e9cile La Grenade]].<ref name=britannica>{{cite encyclopedia| title=Grenada| encyclopedia=Britannica Online Encyclopedia| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/245745/Grenada| accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Jamaica====\n{{main|Monarchy of Jamaica}}\n[[File:Charles Camilla Jamaica 2008.jpg|thumb|right|[[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles, Prince of Wales]] (far left), heir to the [[Monarchy of Jamaica|Jamaican throne]], and his wife, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] (centre), at the Half Moon Hotel, [[Montego Bay]], 13 March 2008]]\nThe monarchy of [[Jamaica]] has its roots in the Spanish monarchy, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the late 16th century, and later the English and then British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 6 August 1962, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Jamaica. The monarch is represented in the country by the [[Governor-General of Jamaica]], Sir [[Patrick Allen (Governor-General)|Patrick Allen]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/jamaica| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Jamaica| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119142220/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/jamaica| archive-date=19 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Jamaica]] [[Portia Simpson-Miller]] has expressed an intention to oversee the process required to change Jamaica to a republic by 2012; she originally stated this would be complete by August of that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamaica plans to become a republic|url=http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=702384&vId=|accessdate=31 December 2011|newspaper=Sky News Australia|date=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jamaica to break links with Queen, says Prime Minister Simpson Miller|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-16449969|accessdate=8 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 January 2012}}</ref> In 2003, former Prime Minister [[P.J. Patterson]], advocated making Jamaica into a republic by 2007.<ref name=republic>{{cite news| last=Staff| title=Jamaica eyes republican future| publisher=BBC| date=22 September 2003| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/3127742.stm| accessdate=14 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Kitts and Nevis====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\nThe monarchy of [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] has its roots in the English and French monarchies, under the authority of which the islands were first colonised in the early 17th century, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 10 June 1973, the country gained independence from the [[United Kingdom]], retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Antigua and Barbuda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.kn/ct.asp?xItem=462&CtNode=58&mp=1|title=About Government|accessdate=18 December 2008|publisher=Government of Saint Kitts and Nevis|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211101312/http://www.gov.kn/ct.asp?xItem=462&CtNode=58&mp=1|archivedate=11 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Kitts and Nevis|Governor-General of Saint Kitts and Nevis]], currently Sir [[Tapley Seaton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-kitts-nevis|title=Country Profile: Saint Kitts and Nevis|accessdate=18 December 2008|work=|publisher=Foreign and Commonwealth Office (UK)|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209005725/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-kitts-nevis|archive-date=9 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Lucia====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Lucia}}\nThe [[Island Caribs|Caribs]] who occupied the island of [[Saint Lucia]] in pre-Columbian times had a complex society, with hereditary kings and shamans. The present monarchy has its roots in the [[Monarchy of the Netherlands|Dutch]], French, and English monarchies, under the authority of which the island was first colonised in 1605, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 22 February 1979, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Saint Lucia.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-lucia?profile=history&pg=3| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Saint Lucia| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=1 January 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121142143/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-lucia?profile=history&pg=3| archive-date=21 January 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Lucia|Governor-General of Saint Lucia]], currently Dame [[Pearlette Louisy]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.stlucia.gov.lc/agencies/office_of_the_governor_general.htm| last=Government Information Service| title=Government of Saint Lucia > Office of the Governor General| publisher=Government of Saint Lucia| accessdate=1 January 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428015619/http://www.stlucia.gov.lc/agencies/office_of_the_governor_general.htm| archivedate=28 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Vincent and the Grenadines====\n{{main|Monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\nThe present monarchy of [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] has its roots in the French monarchy, under the authority of which the island was first colonised in 1719, and later the British monarchy, as a Crown colony. On 27 October 1979, the country gained independence from the United Kingdom, retaining the then reigning monarch, Elizabeth II, as monarch of the newly created monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4928.asp| last=Royal Household at Buckingham Palace| title=The Monarchy Today > Queen and Commonwealth > Other Caribbean Realms| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> The monarch is represented in the country by the [[List of Governors-General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|Governor-General of Vincent and the Grenadines]], currently Sir [[Frederick Ballantyne]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-vincent-grenadines| last=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| authorlink=Foreign and Commonwealth Office| title=Country profiles > North & Central America and Caribbean > Saint Vincent and the Grenadines| publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office| accessdate=18 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205032124/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/about-the-fco/country-profiles/north-central-america/st-vincent-grenadines| archive-date=5 December 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Settled monarchies===\n====Denmark====\n{{main|Monarchy of Denmark}}\n[[File:HakonTheOldAndSkule-Flateyjarbok.jpg|thumb|right|H\u00e1kon, King of Norway (seated on the left) took possession of Greenland in 1261.]]\n[[Greenland]] is one of the three [[Countries of the Kingdom of Denmark|constituent countries]] of the [[Kingdom of Denmark]], with [[Margrethe II of Denmark|Queen Margrethe II]] as the reigning sovereign. The territory first came under monarchical rule in 1261, when the populace accepted the overlordship of the [[Monarchy of Norway|King of Norway]]; by 1380, Norway had entered into a [[personal union]] with the Kingdom of Denmark, which became more entrenched with the union of the kingdoms into [[Denmark\u2013Norway]] in 1536. After the dissolution of this arrangement in 1814, Greenland remained as a Danish colony, and, after [[Greenland in World War II|its role in World War II]], was granted its special status within the Kingdom of Denmark in 1953. The monarch is represented in the territory by the ''[[List of Danish High Commissioners in Greenland|Rigsombudsmand]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stm.dk/Index/dokumenter.asp?o=71&n=1&d=1037&s=2&str=stor |title=Home Rule Act of the Faroe Islands |accessdate=5 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Prime Minister of Denmark |date=}}</ref> ([[High Commissioner]]), [[Mikaela Engell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/print/gl.html |title=Greenland |accessdate=15 January 2009 |work= |publisher=CIA World Factbook |date=}}</ref>\n\n====Netherlands====\n{{main|Monarchy of the Netherlands}}\n[[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Sint Maarten]] are constituent countries of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] and thus have [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|King Willem-Alexander]] as their sovereign, as do the islands of the [[Caribbean Netherlands]]. Aruba was first settled under the authority of the Spanish Crown circa 1499, but was acquired by the Dutch in 1634, under whose control the island has remained, save for an interval between 1805 and 1816, when Aruba was captured by the [[Royal Navy]] of [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]]. The former [[Netherlands Antilles]] were originally discovered by explorers sent in the 1490s by the King of Spain, but were eventually conquered by the [[Dutch West India Company]] in the 17th century, whereafter the islands remained under the control of the Dutch Crown as colonial territories. The Netherlands Antilles achieved the status of an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1954, from which Aruba was split in 1986 as a separate constituent country of the larger kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574919/aruba.html|title=Aruba|accessdate=1 January 2009|publisher=MSN Encarta|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kx8ZpKD5?url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574919/aruba.html|archivedate=1 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The former Netherlands Antilles was dissolved in 2010; two of its islands became constituent countries in their own right ([[Governor of Cura\u00e7ao|Cura\u00e7ao]] and [[Sint Maarten]]), while the other three became integral parts of the [[Netherlands]] (i.e., the Caribbean Netherlands). The monarch is represented in the constituent countries by the [[Governor of Aruba]], [[Alfonso Boekhoudt]], the [[Governor of Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Frits Goedgedrag]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gouverneur.an/index.php?lang=en|title=Who is Governor Frits Goedgedrag?|accessdate=1 January 2009|publisher=Official Website of the Governor of the Netherlands Antilles|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930121255/http://www.gouverneur.an/index.php?lang=en|archivedate=30 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[Governor of Sint Maarten]], [[Eugene Holiday]].\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{main|Monarchy of the United Kingdom}}\nThe United Kingdom possesses a number of [[British overseas territories|overseas territories]] in the Americas, for whom Queen [[Elizabeth II]] is monarch. In North America are [[Anguilla]], [[Bermuda]], the [[British Virgin Islands]], the [[Cayman Islands]], [[Montserrat]], and the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]], while the [[Falkland Islands]], and [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] are located in South America. The [[Caribbean]] islands were colonised under the authority or the direct instruction of a number of European monarchs, mostly [[Monarchy of England|English]], [[Monarchy of the Netherlands|Dutch]], or [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish]], throughout the first half of the 17th century. By 1681, however, when the Turks and Caicos Islands were settled by Britons, all of the above-mentioned islands were under the control of [[Charles II of England|Charles II of England, Scotland, France and Ireland]]. Colonies were merged and split through various reorganizations of the Crown's Caribbean regions, until 19 December 1980, the date that Anguilla became a British Crown territory in its own right. The monarch is represented in these jurisdictions by: the [[Governor of Anguilla]], [[Tim Foy]]; the [[Governor of Bermuda]], [[John Rankin (diplomat)|John Rankin]]; the [[Governor of the British Virgin Islands]], [[Augustus Jaspert|Gus Jaspert]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukinbvi.fco.gov.uk/en/about-us/hm-governor |title=HM Governor |accessdate=5 January 2009 |work= |publisher=HM Government of the British Virgin Islands |date=}}</ref> the [[Governor of the Cayman Islands]], [[Helen Kilpatrick]]; the [[Governor of Montserrat]], [[Andrew Pearce (diplomat)|Andrew Pearce]]; and the [[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands]], [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]].\n\nThe Falkland Islands, off the south coast of [[Argentina]], were simultaneously claimed for [[Louis XV of France]], in 1764, and [[George III of the United Kingdom]], in 1765, though the French colony was ceded to [[Charles III of Spain]] in 1767. By 1833, however, the islands were under full British control. The South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands were discovered by Captain [[James Cook]] for George III in January 1775, and from 1843 were governed by the British Crown-in-Council through the Falkland Islands, an arrangement that stood until the South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands were incorporated as a distinct British overseas territory in 1985. The monarch is represented in these regions by [[Nigel Phillips]], who is both the [[Governor of the Falkland Islands]] and the [[Commissioner for South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Falklands' Swearing in Ceremony for Governor Phillips on 12 September |first= |last= |newspaper=[[MercoPress]] |date= 2017-09-02 |url=http://en.mercopress.com/2017/09/02/falklands-swearing-in-ceremony-for-governor-phillips-on-12-september |accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Succession laws==\n[[File:Succession America.png|thumb|right|\n{{legend|#C89600|[[Primogeniture#Absolute cognatic primogeniture|absolute primogeniture]]}}\n{{legend|#A05050|[[Primogeniture#Male-preference cognatic primogeniture|male-preference cognatic primogeniture]]}}]]\nBefore 28 October 2011, the [[succession order]] in the American Commonwealth realms, as well as those British overseas territories in the Americas, adhered to [[male-preference cognatic primogeniture]], by which succession passed first to an individual's sons, in order of birth, and subsequently to daughters, again in order of birth. However, with the [[Succession to the Throne Act, 2013#Challenges in Canadian courts|possible exception of Canada]], following the legislative changes giving effect to the [[Perth Agreement]], succession is by [[absolute primogeniture]] for those born after 28 October 2011, whereby the eldest child inherits the throne regardless of gender. As these states share the person of their monarch with other countries, all with legislative independence, the change was implemented only once the necessary legal processes were completed in each realm. Those possessions under the Danish and Dutch crowns already adhere to absolute primogeniture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13308 |title=Succession to the throne |accessdate=18 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Dutch Monarchy |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080822054634/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13308 |archivedate = 22 August 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,4310654,00.html Females get the nod in Denmark]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.folketinget.dk/doc.aspx?/Samling/20051/lovforslag/L1/som_vedtaget.htm |title=Suggested changes to the Succession |accessdate=25 January 2009 |publisher=Parliament of Denmark |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204063605/http://www.folketinget.dk/doc.aspx?%2FSamling%2F20051%2Flovforslag%2FL1%2Fsom_vedtaget.htm |archive-date=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead }} (In Danish)</ref>\n\n==Former monarchies==\n[[File:Monumento de Cuauhtemoc.jpg|thumb|left|The monument to [[Cuauht\u00e9moc]], the last sovereign king of the [[Aztec]] Empire]]\nMost [[List of pre-Columbian cultures|pre-Columbian cultures]] of the Americas developed and flourished for centuries under monarchical systems of government. By the time [[European colonization of the Americas|Europeans arrived on the continents]] in the late 15th and early 16th centuries, however, many of these civilizations had ceased to function, due to various natural and artificial causes. Those that remained up to that period were eventually defeated by the agents of European monarchical powers, who, while they remained on the European continent, thereafter established new American administrations overseen by delegated [[viceroy]]s. Some of these colonies were, in turn, replaced by either republican states or locally founded monarchies, ultimately overtaking the entire American holdings of some European monarchs; those crowns that once held or claim territory in the Americas include the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish]], [[List of Portuguese monarchs|Portuguese]], [[List of French monarchs|French]], [[Monarchy of Sweden|Swedish]], and [[List of Russian rulers|Russian]], and even [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Baltic Courland]], [[Holy Roman Emperors|Holy Roman]], [[List of rulers of Prussia|Prussian]] and [[List of Norwegian monarchs|Norwegian]]. Certain of the locally established monarchies were themselves also overthrown through [[revolution]], leaving five current [[Pretender#Americas|pretenders to American thrones]].\n\n===Endemic monarchies===\n====Araucania and Patagonia====\n{{Main|Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia}}\n[[File:Or\u00e9lie Antoine de Tounens.JPG|thumb|right|150px|King [[Or\u00e9lie-Antoine de Tounens|Or\u00e9lie-Antoine I]] of Araucania and Patagonia]]\nThe [[Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia]] was a short-lived attempt at establishing a constitutional monarchy, founded by [[France|French]] lawyer and adventurer [[Orelie-Antoine de Tounens]] in 1860. Nominally, the \"kingdom\" encompassed the present-day  [[Argentina|Argentine]] part of [[Patagonia]] and a small segment of [[Chile]], where [[Mapuche]] peoples were fighting to maintain their sovereignty against the advancing Chilean and Argentine armed forces.<ref name=HistKing>{{cite web| url=http://www.araucania.org/araucania/aukin1_fichiers/aukin1eng.htm| title=Histoiry of the King Orllie-Antoine| publisher=Kingdom of Araucania & Patagonia| accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref>  However, Or\u00e9lie-Antoine never exercised sovereignty over the claimed territory, and his ''de facto'' control was limited to nearly fourteen months and to a small territory around a town called [[Perquenco]] (at the time mainly a Mapuche tent village), which was also the declared capital of his ''kingdom''.\n\nOr\u00e9lie-Antoine felt that the indigenous peoples would be better served in negotiations with the surrounding powers by a European leader,<ref name=HistKing /> and was accordingly elected by a group of Mapuche ''loncos'' (chieftains) to be their king.<ref name=kingdom>{{cite web| url=http://www.araucania.org/| author=Marhique, Huichacurha| title=The Kingdom of Araucania and Patagonia| publisher=Kingdom of Araucania & Patagonia| accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> He made efforts to gain [[Diplomatic recognition|international recognition]], and attempted to involve the French government in his project, but these efforts proved unsuccessful: the French consul concluded that Tounens was insane, and Araucania and Patagonia was never recognized by any country. The Chileans primarily ignored Or\u00e9lie-Antoine and his kingdom, at least initially, and simply went on with the [[occupation of the Araucan\u00eda]], a historical process which concluded in 1883 with Chile establishing control over the region. In the process, Or\u00e9lie-Antoine was captured in 1862, and imprisoned in an insane asylum in Chile. After several fruitless attempts to return to his kingdom (thwarted by Chilean and Argentine authorities), Tounens died penniless in 1878 in [[Tourtoirac]], France. A recent pretender, [[Jean-Michel Parasiliti di Para|Prince Antoine IV]], lived in France until 2017. The previous pretender renounced his claims to the Patagonian throne,<ref>{{cite book| last=Men\u00e9ndez| first=Braun| title=Peque\u00f1a historia patag\u00f3nica| publisher=Emec\u00e9 Editores| year=1959| page=128|language=Spanish}}</ref> even though a few Mapuches continue to recognise the Araucanian monarchy.<ref name=kingdom />\n\n====Aztec====\n{{Main|Aztec Empire}}\nThe [[Aztec]] [[Empire]] existed in the central [[Mexico|Mexican]] region between c. 1325 and 1521, and was formed by [[Aztec Triple Alliance|the triple alliance]] of the ''[[Tlatoani|tlatoque]]'' (the [[Nahuatl]] term for \"speaker\", also translated in [[English language|English]] as \"king\") of three [[city-state]]s: [[Tlacopan]], [[Texcoco (altepetl)|Texcoco]], and the capital of the empire, [[Tenochtitlan]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Concise History of Mexico |last=Hamnett |first=Brian R. |publisher=Cambridge University Press |url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn/page/51 51] |quote=Aztec Triple Alliance. |accessdate=2 January 2009|isbn=978-0-521-58916-1 |year=1999 }}</ref> While the lineage of Tenochtitlan's kings continued after [[Fall of Tenochtitlan|the city's fall to the Spanish]] on 13 August 1521, they reigned as [[Puppet state|puppet rulers]] of the [[Monarchy of Spain|King of Spain]] until the death of the last dynastic ''tlatoani'', [[Luis de Santa Mar\u00eda Nanacacipactzin]], on 27 December 1565.<ref>{{cite book |title=Codex Chimalpahin |last=de San Ant\u00f3n Mu\u00f1\u00f3n Chimalpahin Cuauhtlehuanitzin |first=Domingo Francisco |author2=Arthur J. O. Anderson |author3=Susan Schroeder |author4=Wayne Ruwet  |year=1997 |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |isbn=978-0-8061-2950-1 |page=43 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RSNdzTEHU_sC&pg=PA43&dq=Luis+de+Santa+Mar%C3%ADa+Nanacacipactzin}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\n{{Main|Empire of Brazil|United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves}}\n[[File:Maria I, Vieira.jpg|thumb|left|190px|[[Maria I of Portugal]] became the first [[list of monarchs of Brazil|Queen of Brazil]] in 1815 with the creation of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]].]]\n[[File:Pedro Am\u00e9rico - D. Pedro II na abertura da Assembl\u00e9ia Geral.jpg|180px|thumb|right|Emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil]]]]\nBrazil was created as a kingdom on 16 December 1815, when [[John VI of Portugal|Prince Jo\u00e3o]], [[Princes of Brazil|Prince of Brazil]], who was then acting as [[regent]] for his ailing mother, [[Maria I of Portugal|Queen Maria]], elevated the colony to a [[Constituent state|constituent country]] of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Vianna | first = H\u00e9lio | title = Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil: per\u00edodo colonial, monarquia e rep\u00fablica | publisher = Melhoramentos | year = 1994 | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | isbn = |language=Spanish}}</ref> While the royal court was still based in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Jo\u00e3o ascended as king of the united kingdom the following year, and returned to Portugal in 1821,<ref name=Pedro1>{{cite web| url=http://historicaltextarchive.com/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=427| author=Miller, James| title=Pedro II, Emperor of Brazil| publisher=Historical Text Archive| accessdate=17 December 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222184450/http://historicaltextarchive.com/sections.php?op=viewarticle&artid=427| archive-date=22 February 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref> leaving his son, [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]], Prince Royal, as his regent in the [[Kingdom of Brazil]]. In September of that same year, the Portuguese parliament threatened to diminish Brazil back to the status of a colony, dismantle all the royal agencies in Rio de Janeiro, and demanded Pedro return to [[Lisbon]].<ref name=Pedro1 /> The Prince, however, feared these moves would trigger separatist movements and refused to comply; instead, at the urging of his father, he [[Brazilian Declaration of Independence|declared Brazil an independent Nation]] on 7 September 1822, leading to the formation of the [[Empire of Brazil]], a constitutional monarchy. \n\nPrince Pedro became the first Emperor of Brazil on 12 October 1822, with the title of Pedro I (on that date, he was formally offered the Throne of the newly created Empire, accepted it, and was acclaimed as monarch), and his coronation took place on 1 December 1822.<ref>{{cite book| last=Vainfas| first=Ronaldo| title=Dicion\u00e1rio do Brasil Imperial| publisher=Objetiva| year=2002| location=Rio de Janeiro|language=Spanish}}</ref> After Pedro [[Abdication|abdicated]] the throne on 7 April 1831, the Brazilian empire saw only one additional monarch: [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro II]],<ref name=Pedro1 /> who reigned for 58 years before a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] overthrew the monarchy on 15 November 1889. There are two pretenders to the defunct Brazilian throne: [[Prince Luiz of Orl\u00e9ans-Braganza]], head of the Vassouras branch of the [[Brazilian Imperial Family]], and, according to legitimist claims, ''de jure'' Emperor of Brazil; and [[Prince Pedro Carlos of Orl\u00e9ans-Braganza]], head of the [[Petr\u00f3polis]] line of the Brazilian Imperial Family, and heir to the Brazilian throne according to royalists.<ref>{{cite newspaper| author=Handler, Bruce| date= 5 March 1989| title=Brazil to Decide on Return of Monarchy| journal=Los Angeles Times| page=34 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-03-05/news/mn-199_1_vote-set |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nThe Brazilian constitution of 1988 called for a general vote on the restoration of the monarchy, which was [[Brazilian constitutional referendum, 1993|held in 1993]]. The royalists went to the polls divided, with the press indicating there were actually two princes aspiring to the Brazilian throne (Dom Luiz de Orleans e Bragan\u00e7a and Dom Jo\u00e3o Henrique); this created some confusion among the voters.\n\n====Haiti====\n{{Main|First Empire of Haiti|Second Empire of Haiti|Kingdom of Haiti}}\nThe entire island of [[Hispaniola]] was first claimed on 5 December 1492, by [[Christopher Columbus]], for [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabella]], and the first Viceroy of the Americas was established along with a number of colonies throughout the Island. With the later discovery of Mexico and Peru many of the early settlers left for the main land, but some twelve cities and a hundred thousand souls remained, mainly in the Eastern part of the Island. Through the Treaty of Riswick in 1697, [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]] received the western third of the Island  from Spain as retribution and formalized the first French pirate settlement in existence since the mid-1600s,<ref>{{cite web| first=Richard A.| last=Haggerty| title=Haiti, A Country Study: French Settlement and Sovereignty| url=http://countrystudies.us/haiti/7.htm| publisher=US Library of Congress| year=1989| accessdate=30 March 2008}}</ref> with the colony administered by [[Gouverneur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|a governor-general representing the French crown]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?BioId=35359| title=Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online > Emmanuel-Auguste de Cahideuc, Comte Dubois de la Motte| publisher=University of Toronto/Universit\u00e9 Laval |accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> an arrangement that stood until the [[French Revolution]] toppled the monarchy of France on 21 September 1792. Though the French government retained control over the region of [[Saint-Domingue]], on 22 September 1804, [[Jean-Jacques Dessalines]], who had served as Governor-General of Saint-Domingue since 30 November 1803, declared himself as head of an independent [[Empire of Haiti (1804\u20131806)|Empire of Haiti]], with his coronation as Emperor Jacques I taking place on 6 October that year. After his assassination on 17 October 1806, the country was split in half, the northern portion eventually becoming the [[Kingdom of Haiti]] on 28 March 1811, with [[Henri Christophe]] installed as King Henri I.<ref name=ceac>{{cite book| last=Cheesman| first=Clive| title=The Armorial of Haiti| publisher=The College of Arms| year=2007| location=London| url=http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/| isbn=978-0-9506980-2-1| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> When King Henri committed suicide on 8 October 1820, and his son, [[Jacques-Victor Henry, Prince Royal of Haiti]], was murdered by revolutionaries ten days later, the kingdom was merged into the southern Republic of Haiti, of which [[Faustin I of Haiti|Faustin-\u00c9lie Soulouque]] was elected [[President of Haiti|president]] on 2 March 1847. Two years later, on 26 August 1849, the [[National Assembly of Haiti|Haitian national assembly]] declared the president as Emperor Faustin I, thereby re-establishing the Empire of Haiti. But this monarchical reincarnation was to be short lived as well, as a revolution broke out in the empire in 1858, resulting in Faustin abdicating the throne on 18 January 1859.<ref>{{cite book| first=Jan| last=Rogozinski| year=1999| title=A Brief History of the Caribbean| edition=Revised| publisher=Facts on File, Inc.| location=New York| page=[https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofca00rogo_0/page/220 220]| isbn=0-8160-3811-2| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofca00rogo_0/page/220}}</ref>\n\n====Inca====\n{{Main|Inca Empire}}\n[[File:TupacamaruI.JPG|thumb|160px|right|[[T\u00fapac Amaru]], the last ''Sapa Inca'' of the [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]]]]\nThe [[Inca Empire]] spread across the north western parts of South America between 1438 and 1533, ruled over by a monarch addressed as the [[Sapa Inca|''Sapa Inca'', ''Sapa'', or ''Apu'']]. The [[Inca civilization]] emerged in the [[Kingdom of Cusco]], and expanded to become the ''Ttahuantin-suyu'', or \"land of the four sections\", each ruled by a governor or viceroy called ''Apu-cuna'', under the leadership of the central ''Sapa Inca''. The Inca Empire eventually fell to the Spanish in 1533, when the last ''Sapa Inca'' of the empire, [[Atahualpa]], was captured and executed on 29 August.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761560004_3/Inca_Empire.html#s12 |title=Inca Empire: Spanish Conquest |accessdate=2 January 2009 |publisher=MSN Encarta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kyWmnijq?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761560004_3/Inca_Empire.html|archivedate=2 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The conquerors installed other ''Sapa Inca'' beginning with Atahualpa's brother, [[T\u00fapac Huallpa]]. [[Manco Inca Yupanqui]], originally also a puppet Inca Emperor installed by the Spaniards, rebelled and founded the small independent [[Neo-Inca State]] in [[Vilcabamba, Peru|Vilcabamba]], and the line continued until the death of [[T\u00fapac Amaru]] in 1572.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761593238/amar%C3%BA_tupac.html |title=T\u00fapac Amaru |accessdate=19 January 2009 |publisher=MSN Encarta |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kx7Qgcer?url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761593238/amar%C3%BA_tupac.html|archivedate=1 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Maya====\n{{Main|Maya Civilization}}\nThe [[Maya civilization]] was located on the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] and into the [[Isthmus|isthmian]] portion of North America, and the northern portion of [[Central America]] (Guatemala, Belize, El Salvador and Honduras) was formed of a number of ''ajawil'', ''ajawlel'', or ''ajawlil''\u2013 hierarchical polities headed by an hereditary ruler known as a ''[[Ajaw|kuhul ajaw]]'' (the [[Mayan languages|Mayan]] term indicating a sovereign leader).{{#tag:ref|Both terms appear in early Colonial texts (including ''Papeles de Paxbol\u00f3n'') where they are used as synonymous to Aztec and Spanish terms for supreme rulers and their domains \u2013 ''tlahtoani'' (''[[Tlatoani]]'') and ''tlahtocayotl'', ''rey'', or ''magestad'' and ''reino'', ''se\u00f1or'' and ''se\u00f1or\u00edo'', or ''dominio''.|group=N|name=Maya1}} Despite constant warfare and shifts in regional power, most [[Maya civilization#Political structures|Maya kingdoms]] remained a part of the region's landscape, even following subordination to hegemonic rulers through conquest or dynastic union. Nonetheless, the Maya civilization began its decline in the 8th and 9th centuries, and by the time of the arrival of the Spanish, only a few kingdoms remained, such as the [[Peten Itza kingdom]], [[Mam people|Mam]], [[Kaqchikel people|Kaqchikel]], and the [[K'iche' Kingdom of Q'umarkaj]]. On 13 March 1697, the last [[Itza]] Maya king was [[Spanish conquest of Pet\u00e9n#Fall of Nojpet\u00e9n|defeated at Nojpet\u00e9n]] by the forces of King [[Philip IV of Spain]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Ancient Maya |last=Sharer |first=Robert J. |author2=Sylvanus Griswold Morley |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-2130-1 |page=423 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=c65_g571LyAC&pg=PA423&lpg=PA423&dq=1697+Tayasal |year=1994 }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n{{Main|First Mexican Empire|Second Mexican Empire}}\nWith the victory of the [[Mexico|Mexicans]] over the Spanish imperial army in 1821, the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain]] came to a conclusion. The newly independent [[Congress of Mexico|Mexican Congress]] still desired that [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|King Ferdinand VII]], or another member of the [[House of Bourbon]], agree to be installed as Emperor of Mexico, thereby forming a type of [[personal union]] with Spain. The Spanish monarchy, however, refused to recognise the new state, and decreed that it would allow no other European prince to take the throne of Mexico. Thus, the Mexican [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide]] was crowned as Augustine I on 19 May 1822, with an official decree of confirmation issued two days following. Only a few months later, Augustine dissolved a factious congress, thereby prompting an enraged [[Antonio L\u00f3pez de Santa Anna]] to mount a coup, which led to the declaration of a republic on 1 December 1822. In order to end the unrest, Augustine abdicated on 19 March 1823 and left the country, and the Mexican monarchy was abolished. After hearing that the situation in Mexico had only grown worse since his abdication, Iturbide returned from England on 11 May 1824, but was detained upon setting foot in Mexico and, without trial, was executed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/379167/Mexico/27357/The-Mexican-Empire-1821-23 |title=History \u00bb Independence \u00bb The Mexican Empire, 1821\u201323 |accessdate=2 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date=}}</ref>\n[[File:X-Large Portrait of Maximiliano.jpg|170px|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I of Mexico]], by [[Franz Xaver Winterhalter]]]]\n\n[[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], elected as [[President of Mexico]] on 19 January 1858, suspended all repayments on Mexico's foreign debts (save those owed to the [[United States]]), leading France, the United Kingdom, and Spain to send a joint expeditionary force that took [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz]] in December 1861. Ju\u00e1rez then repaid the debts, after which British and Spanish troops withdrew, but Emperor [[Napoleon III of France]] used the situation as a pretext to overthrow the republic and install a monarch friendly to the interests of France. Archduke Maximilian, brother of the [[Emperor of Austria]], was elevated as [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico]], thereby re-establishing the Mexican monarchy, but the new emperor ultimately did not bow to Napoleon's wishes, leading the latter to withdraw the majority of his influence from Mexico. Regardless, Maximilian was still viewed as a French puppet, and an illegitimate leader of the country. As well, at the end of the [[American Civil War]], US troops moved to the Mexico-US border as part of a planned invasion, seeing the establishment of the Second Mexican Empire as an infringement on their [[Monroe Doctrine]]. Backed by the Americans, ex-president Ju\u00e1rez mobilised to retake power, and defeated Maximilian at [[Quer\u00e9taro, Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]] on 15 May 1867. The Emperor was arraigned before a military tribunal, sentenced to death, and executed at the ''Cerro de las Campanas'' on 19 June 1867.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/379167/Mexico/27361/French-intervention |title=History \u00bb Independence \u00bb French intervention |accessdate=2 January 2009 |work= |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date=}}</ref>\n\n====Miskito====\nThe [[Miskito people|Miskito]] people of Central America were governed by the authority of a monarch, but one who shared his royal powers with a governor and a general. The origins of the monarchy are unknown; however, its sovereignty was lost when King Edward I of the Miskito Nation signed the [[Treaty of Friendship and Alliance]] with King [[George II of the United Kingdom]], putting the Miskito kingdom under the [[British protectorate|British protection]] and law. At the cessation of the [[American Revolutionary War]], King [[George III of the United Kingdom]], via the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]], relinquished control of the Miskito's lands, though Britain continued an unofficial protectorate over the kingdom to protect Miskito interests against Spanish encroachments. After British interest in the region waned, [[Nicaragua]] dissolved and occupied the Miskito kingdom in 1894,<ref>{{cite news| first=Rory| last=Carroll| title=Nicaragua's green lobby is leaving rainforest people 'utterly destitute'| date=26 November 2006| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2006/nov/26/famine.conservation| work=Guardian Unlimited|accessdate=7 September 2007 | location=London}}</ref> with the monarch thereafter becoming known as the Hereditary Chief. [[Norton Cuthbert Clarence]] is the current pretender to the Miskito Kingdom and Hereditary Chief of the Miskito Nation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Penny Ante Imperialism: The Mosquito Shore and the Bay of Honduras |last=Naylor |first=Robert A.  |publisher= University of Virginia |isbn=978-0-8386-3323-6 |page=310 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eJ8WAAAAYAAJ |year=1989 }}</ref>\n\n====Ta\u00edno====\nThe [[Ta\u00edno people|Ta\u00edno]]s were an indigenous civilization spread across those islands today lying within the [[Bahamas]], [[Greater Antilles]], and the northern [[Lesser Antilles]]. These regions were divided into kingdoms (the island of [[Hispaniola]] alone was segmented into five kingdoms), which were themselves sometimes sub-divided into provinces. Each kingdom was led by a ''[[cacique]]'', or \"chieftain\", who was advised in his exercise of royal power by a council of priests/healers known as ''bohiques''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html| title=Caciques, nobles and their regalia| accessdate=9 November 2006| publisher=elmuseo.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061009090513/http://elmuseo.org/taino/caciques.html |archivedate = 9 October 2006}}</ref> The line of succession, however, was [[matrilineal]], whereby if there was no male heir to become ''cacigue'', the title would pass to the eldest child, whether son or daughter, of the deceased's sister.<ref name=Rouse>{{cite book| last=Rouse| first=Irving| title=The Tainos: Rise and Decline of the people who greeted Columbus| url=https://archive.org/details/tainosrisedeclin00rous| url-access=registration| year=1992| publisher=Yale University Press| location=New York| isbn=0-300-05696-6}}</ref> After battling for centuries with the [[Island Caribs|Carib]], the Ta\u00edno empire finally succumbed to disease and genocide brought by the Spanish colonisers.<ref>{{cite book| last=Sale| first=Kirkpatrick| title=The Conquest of Paradise| page=157| isbn=0-333-57479-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/580786/Taino| title=Ta\u00edno people| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica| accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Colonial monarchies===\n====Courland====\n[[File:Jacob Kettler.gif|170px|thumb|right|Jacob Kettler, Duke of Courland and Semigallia tried to established a colony in the Americas.]]\n{{main|Duchy of Courland and Semigallia}}\nAfter a number of failed attempts at colonising [[Tobago]], Duke [[Jacob Kettler]] of [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Courland and Semigallia]] sent one more ship to the island, which landed there on 20 May 1654, carrying soldiers and colonists, who named the island ''[[Courland colonization of the Americas|New Courland]]''. At approximately the same time, Dutch colonies were established at other locations on the island, and eventually outgrew those of the Duchy of Courland in population. When the Duke was captured by Swedish forces in 1658, Dutch settlers overtook the Courland colonies, forcing the Governor to surrender. After a return of the territory to Courland through the 1660 [[Treaty of Oliwa]], a number of attempts were made by the next Duke of Courland (Friedrich Casimir Kettler) at re-colonisation, but these met with failure, and he sold New Courland in 1689.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.colonialvoyage.com/tobago.html| title=Dutch Portuguese Colonial History > Dutch and Courlanders in Tobago| publisher=Colonialvoyage.com| accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====France====\nAfter [[Francis I of France|King Francis I]] commissioned [[Jacques Cartier]] to search out an eastern route to [[Asia]], the city of [[Port Royal, Annapolis County, Nova Scotia|Port Royal]] was founded on 27 July 1605 in what is today [[Nova Scotia]]. From there, the French Crown's empire in the Americas grew to include areas of land surrounding the [[Great Lakes]] and down the [[Mississippi River]], as well as islands in the Caribbean, and the [[French Guiana|north eastern shore of South America]]; the [[New France|Viceroyalty of New France]] was eventually made into a royal province of France in 1663 by [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]].<ref>{{cite journal| last=Emerson| first=Rupert| title=Colonialism and Decolonization| journal=Journal of Contemporary History| volume=4| issue=1| pages=3\u201316| date=January 1969| doi=10.1177/002200946900400101}}</ref> Some regions were lost to the Spanish or British Crowns through conflict and treaties, and those that were still possessions of the French king on 21 December 1792 came under republican rule when the French monarchy was abolished on that day.<ref>{{Cite book| first=Christopher| last=Hibbert| title=The Days of the French Revolution| year=1980| location=New York| publisher=Quill, William Morrow| url=https://books.google.com/?id=yr1z38HCkdAC&dq=Hibbert+French+Revolution| isbn=0-688-03704-6| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| first=Georges| last=Lefebvre| title=The French Revolution: From Its Origins to 1793| year=1971| publisher=Columbia University Press| url=https://books.google.com/?id=I2oA5MtB0ZkC&dq=Lefebvre+estates+general| isbn=0-231-08598-2| accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref>\nUpon several restorations of the monarchy, the royal presence in the Americas ended with the collapse of the [[Second French Empire]] under [[Napoleon III]] in 1870.\n\n====Holy Roman Empire of German Nationalities====\n{{main|Holy Roman Empire}}\n[[File:Quaterionenadler David de Negker.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.15|Double-headed eagle with coats of arms of individual states, the symbol of the Holy Roman Empire (painting from 1510)]]\nMost important of Holy Roman Emperors Clan later named after [[Habsburg Castle|Habsburg]] in Swiss Aargau descends from [[Africa]], and its first named [[ancestor]] is [[Heracles]]. The period in which [[Habsburg|Habsburg Dynasty]] has been ruling [[Spanish Habsburg|Spain]], [[Spanish Netherlands|The Netherlands]], [[History of Germany|Germany]], [[History of Austria|Austria]] and other Central European Regions from the [[Renaissance]] on is named [[Spanish Golden Age|The Golden Age]]. This period of [[Conquistador|Conquistatores]] after [[Catholicos|Rey Catolicos]] who fought in [[Reconquista]] against [[Al-Andalus|Spanish Islam]] and [[Sephardi Jews|Sephards]], who moved back to [[Maghreb|Africa]], The Spanish Netherlands or to the exceptional tolerant [[Ottoman Empire]] of its time. The [[Kingdom of Spain]] underwent enormous economic growth by virtue of its colonies in [[Americas|South America]]. [[Cadiz]] city of the [[Phoenicians]] also named oldest of the European towns and later the place to start [[C\u00e1diz (Parliament of Andalusia constituency)|Spanish Parlament]] and [[Seville]] were the most priviliged cities, because of their location in the [[Iberian Peninsula|Western Iberian Peninsula]]. Monuments like [[Christopher Columbus|Cristoforo Colombo Epitaph]] and Seville Cathedral with its famous Giralda of [[Abu Yusuf Yaqub al-Mansur]] can be seen as a sign for [[Rinascimento]] still today and in the future. [[Prussia|Prussian Colonies]] of the 18 century were f.e. Fredericksburg in Ghana and some other small settlements of Austrian Marie-Therese Habsburg in Africa but also in [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands|South Asia]]. Therefore Trade and Knowledge Exchange always existed between [[Americas]] and the Roman Empire of German Nation, especially under der Rule of [[Karl V|Charles V]] [[Plus Ultra]] by help of Merchantise families as [[Welser]] and the [[Fugger]] of Augsburg and Nurnberg in [[Bavaria]] in South Germany. As Hightech can be seen [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]] Arts, [[Johannes Gutenberg|Printing Press Progress]] and spread of [[Lutheranism|Luterhan Church]], not only in Europe but also within the [[Indians]] in the Americas and Global. People of all professional backgrounds were migrating to find their new luck to fulfil their dreams not only in the past but, remember spread of [[food culture]], still today. [[Coat of arms of Spain|Spanish Coat of Arms]] still expresses the curiosity of a continent around 1500.\nEnd of Europeans Wealth Unity can be seen in the Siege of [[Elizabeth I of England]] against the [[Armada]] in the Atlantic and perhaps a slowdown of Continental Europe Power against United Kingdom and its [[Commonwealth]]. After [[Bourbon Spain|Bourbon Emperor]] gained Spanish Crown by [[Duke of marlborough|Duke of Marlboroughs]] Siege against glorious [[Prince Eugene of Savoy|Eugene of Savoia]], Habsburgs most important warhero, Central Europe only was assumed to get back trading power by construction of [[Suez Canal|Canal of Suez]]. But also migration from central Europe to [[Russia]] and Asia, which was most famously reached by [[Hanse]] on [[Baltic Sea]] and on the way to [[Black Sea]] and beyond. Therefore see rich and diverse Russian History reflected also in many German expressions still in the Russian language. In between Germans were always many other European Nations as [[Jewish People|Jewish Populations]], [[Romani People]] and important for Arts the [[Italian artists]] moving all over the world to spread adequate styles for [[Noblepeople|Nobles]], not to forget [[Music baroque|Musicians]]. Austrias last colony was [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Mexico of Maximilian]] and Germany had to leave Africa and Oceania after [[World War I|WorldWarI]] and its tragic loose of powers. Because these disasters ended in another even more cruel war and unique [[Cold War]] which gained their Happy End in Summer 1989 by [[Fall of the Wall]]. So not only shadow of [[Karl Habsburg|Karl I Habsburg]] loosing Austrian Habsburg Empire and his death in Madeira, but more Ottomans loosing power in one of the oldest multinational Empires of the world can still to be recognised in todays conflicts globally. Following [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilians I]] theme ''Tu Felix Austria Nube..'' some of the glorious family were happily married in Brazil too. Therefore not only because of [[Latin Church]] and some islands of luck in where local identity could resist Technical Progress and newer influences a strong [[Feelgood|feelgood]] connection may be assumed.\n\n\n[[File:Alexander II of Russia by K.Makovskiy (1881, GTG).jpg|170px|thumb|left|[[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]], Emperor of Russia, who sold Alaska to the United States of America in 1867]]\n\n====Russia====\n{{main|Russian Empire}}\nThe first permanent Russian settlements in what is today the US state of [[Alaska]] were set down in the 1790s, forming [[Russian Alaska]], after [[Russian Czar|Tsar]] [[Peter I of Russia|Peter I]] called for expeditions across the [[Bering Strait]] in 1725,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://kodiakisland.net/timeline.html| title=Alaska History Timeline| publisher=Kodiak Island Internet Directory| accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> with the region administered by the head of the [[Russian-American Company]] as the Emperor's representative. Another Russian outpost, [[Fort Ross, California|Fort Ross]], was established in 1812 in what is now [[California]].<ref>{{cite book| last=Nordlander| first=David J.| title=For God & Tsar: A Brief History of Russian America 1741\u20131867| publisher=Alaska Natural History Association| location=Anchorage| year=1994| isbn=0-930931-15-7}}</ref> The colonies, however, were never profitable enough to maintain Russian interest in the area, with the population only ever reaching a maximum of 700. Fort Ross was sold in 1841, and in 1867, a deal was brokered whereby [[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]] sold his Alaskan territory to the United States of America for $7,200,000, and the official transfer took place on 30 October that year.<ref>{{cite book| last=Farrar| first=Victor John| title=The Annexation of Russian America to the United States| publisher=Russell & Russell| location=New York| year=1966}}</ref>\n\n====Portugal====\n[[File:Maria I, Vieira.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Queen [[Maria I of Portugal]], first [[Kingdom of Brazil|Queen of Brazil]] and the only European monarch to have been born in the Americas.]]\n{{main|Portuguese Empire}}\nThe United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves came into being in the wake of Portugal's war with [[Napoleonic France]]. The Portuguese Prince Regent, the future King John VI, with his incapacitated mother, Queen [[Maria I of Portugal]] and the Royal Court, [[Transfer of the Portuguese Court to Brazil|escaped]] to the [[colony of Brazil]] in 1808.\nWith the defeat of Napoleon in 1815, there were calls for the return of the Portuguese Monarch to Lisbon; the Portuguese Prince Regent enjoyed life in Rio de Janeiro, where the monarchy was at the time more popular and where he enjoyed more freedom, and he was thus unwilling to return to Europe. However, those advocating the return of the Court to Lisbon argued that Brazil was only a colony and that it was not right for Portugal to be governed from a colony. On the other hand, leading Brazilian courtiers pressed for the elevation of Brazil from the rank of a colony, so that they could enjoy the full status of being nationals of the mother-country. Brazilian nationalists also supported the move, because it indicated that Brazil would no longer be submissive to the interests of Portugal, but would be of equal status within a transatlantic monarchy.\n\n====Spain====\n{{main|Monarchy of Spain}}\nBeginning in 1492 with the voyages of [[Christopher Columbus]] under the direction of [[Isabella I of Castile]], the [[Monarchy of Spain|Spanish Crown]] amassed a large [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|American empire]] over three centuries, spreading first from the [[Caribbean]] to [[Central America]], most of [[South America]], [[Mexico]], what is today the [[Southwestern United States]], and the Pacific coast of [[North America]] up to [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartroli |first=Tom\u00e1s |title=Presencia hisp\u00e1nica en la costa noroeste de Am\u00e9rica |publisher=Universidad de British Columbio |location=Vancouver |year=1968|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first=Angelina |last=Mir\u00f3 |title=Catalans a la costa oest del Canad\u00e0: Els catalans a la Col\u00fambia Brit\u00e0nica al s.XVIII |url=http://www.histocat.cat/pdf/catalans_al_canada.pdf |accessdate=19 December 2008 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030000815/http://www.histocat.cat/pdf/catalans_al_canada.pdf |archivedate=30 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> These regions formed the majority of the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain]], the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]], the [[Viceroyalty of New Granada]], and the [[Viceroyalty of the R\u00edo de la Plata]] in each of which the Spanish monarch was represented by [[List of viceroys of New Spain|a viceroy]]. By the early 19th century, however, the Spanish sovereign's possessions in the Americas began a series of independence movements, which culminated in the Crown's loss of all its colonies on the mainland of North and South America by 1825. The remaining colonies of [[Cuba]] and [[Puerto Rico]] were occupied by the [[United States]] following the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], ending Spanish rule in the Americas by 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=Mexico and the United States |last=Lee |first=Stacey |publisher=Marshall Cavendish |isbn=978-0-7614-7402-9 |page=777 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSzyMGh8pNwC&pg=PA777&dq=spanish+empire+in+1899+spanish+american |date=October 2002}}</ref>\n\n====Sweden====\n{{main|Monarchy of Sweden}}\nFor a period of time the French ceded sovereignty of the island of [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] to the Swedes but it was eventually returned. Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (1784\u20131878) was operated as a porto Franco (free port). The capital city of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] retains its Swedish name.\n\n===Self-proclaimed monarchies===\n[[File:James Strang daguerreotype (1856).jpg|thumb|125px|1856 [[daguerreotype]] of James Strang]]\nThese entities were never recognized ''de jure'' as legitimate governments, but still sometimes exercised a certain degree of local control or influence within their respective locations until the death of their \"monarch\":\n\n;James J. Strang\n[[James Strang]], a would-be successor to the [[Latter Day Saints|Mormon]] prophet [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]], proclaimed himself \"king\" over his [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)|church]] in 1850, which was then concentrated mostly on [[Beaver Island (Lake Michigan)|Beaver Island]] in [[Lake Michigan]].  On 8 July of that year, he was physically crowned in an elaborate coronation ceremony complete with crown, sceptre, throne, ermine robe and breastplate.<ref>Weeks, Robert P. \"For His Was the Kingdom, and the Power, and the Glory...Briefly\" ''American Heritage'' 21 (4).  The sceptre is preserved in the vault of the archives of the [[Community of Christ]] church in Independence, Missouri; the whereabouts of Strang's remaining regalia is a mystery.</ref>  Although he never claimed legal sovereignty over Beaver Island or any other geographical entity, Strang managed (as a member of the [[Michigan State Legislature]]) to have his \"kingdom\" constituted as a separate [[Manitou County, Michigan|county]], where his followers held all county offices, and Strang's word was law.  U.S. President [[Millard Fillmore]] ordered an investigation into Strang's colony, which resulted in Strang's trial in [[Detroit]] for [[treason]], trespass, [[counterfeiting]] and other crimes, but the jury found the \"king\" innocent of all charges.  Strang was eventually assassinated by two disgruntled followers in 1856, and his kingdom&mdash;together with his royal regalia&mdash;vanished.\n\n;Joshua Norton\n[[Emperor Norton|Joshua Abraham Norton]], an Englishman who emigrated to [[San Francisco]], [[California]] in 1849, proclaimed himself \"Emperor of These United States\" in 1859, later adding the title \"Protector of Mexico\".  Though never recognized by the U.S. or Mexican governments, he was accorded a certain degree of deference within San Francisco itself, including reserved balcony seats (for which he was never charged) at local theatres, and salutes by policemen who passed him on the street.  Specially printed currency authorized by Norton was accepted as [[legal tender]] within several businesses in the city.  When Norton died in 1880, he was given a lavish funeral attended by over 30,000 persons.<ref>[http://www.emperornorton.net/NortonI-Cowan.html Norton I, Emperor of the United States and Protector of Mexico]</ref>\n\n;James Harden-Hickey\n[[James Harden-Hickey]] was a self-proclaimed prince, who attempted to establish the so-called [[Principality of Trinidad]] on [[Trindade Island|Trindade]] and the [[Martim Vaz Islands]] in the South Atlantic Ocean during the late 19th century. Although initially garnering some newspaper attention, Hickey's claims were ignored or ridiculed by other nations, and the islands eventually were occupied by military forces from nearby Brazil which remain there to the present day.\n\n;Matthew Dowdy Shiell\nA self-proclaimed monarch of the so-called [[Kingdom of Redonda]], an island in the [[Caribbean Sea]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}  Whether Shiell ever actually claimed to be king of this tiny islet is open to debate; however, other individuals later claimed the title of \"King of Redonda,\" without having apparently ever tried to physically establish themselves on the island itself.{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Afro-Bolivian monarchy]]\n* [[Canadian Confederation]]\n* [[List of monarchs in the Americas]]\n* [[List of the last monarchs in the Americas]]\n* [[Monarchies in Africa]]\n* [[Monarchies in Europe]]\n* [[Monarchies in Oceania]]\n* [[Monarchism]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | author=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] | date=11 July 2006 | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/index.html | title=CIA \u2014 The World Factbook | work=[[The World Factbook]] | accessdate=25 November 2008 }}\n* {{cite web | author=Central Intelligence Agency | date=18 July 2006 | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/world-leaders-1/index.html | title=World Leaders | work=[[World Leaders]] | accessdate=25 November 2008 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{American monarchies}}\n{{Monarchies}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monarchies In The Americas}}\n[[Category:Americas]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of North America| ]]\n[[Category:Monarchies of South America| ]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: loosing->losing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monarchies_in_the_Americas"}
{"title_page": "Jim McCusker (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Jim McCusker\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = James McCusker<ref name = \"Hugman\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1939|12|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Maghera]], Northern Ireland\n|height      = \n|position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|youthyears1 = 1956\u20131957\n|youthclubs1 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|years1      = 1957\u20131959\n|clubs1      = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|caps1       = 7\n|goals1      = 0\n|years2      = 1959\u20131960\n|clubs2      = [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]\n|caps2       = 2\n|goals2      = 0\n|totalcaps   = 9\n|totalgoals  = 0\n}}\n'''James McCusker''' (born 27 December 1939) is a Northern Irish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Maghera]],<ref name = \"Hugman\">{{Hugman|12349|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref> McAlea McCusker [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as an amateur in December 1956.<ref name = \"F401\">Frost, p. 401</ref> He joined the first team in February 1957.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/> He made 7 league appearances for the club.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/><ref>Frost, p. 385</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/bradfordcity/bradfordcity.html|title=BRADFORD CITY : 1946/47 - 2013/14|accessdate=5 December 2018|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database}}</ref> He left the club to join [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] in August 1959,<ref name = \"F401\"/> for whom he made a further 2 league appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/stockport/stockport.html|title=STOCKPORT COUNTY : 1946/47 - 2010/11|accessdate=5 December 2018|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Frost|first=Terry|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988|publisher=Breedon Books Sport|year=1988|isbn=0-907969-38-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCusker, Jim}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association footballers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n\n\n{{NorthernIreland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Jim McCusker\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = James McCusker<ref name = \"Hugman\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1939|12|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Maghera]], Northern Ireland\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|height      = \n|position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|youthyears1 = 1956\u20131957\n|youthclubs1 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|years1      = 1957\u20131959\n|clubs1      = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|caps1       = 7\n|goals1      = 0\n|years2      = 1959\u20131960\n|clubs2      = [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]\n|caps2       = 2\n|goals2      = 0\n|totalcaps   = 9\n|totalgoals  = 0\n}}\n'''James McCusker''' (born 27 December 1939) is a Northern Irish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Maghera]],<ref name = \"Hugman\">{{Hugman|12349|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref> McAlea McCusker [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as an amateur in December 1956.<ref name = \"F401\">Frost, p. 401</ref> He joined the first team in February 1957.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/> He made 7 league appearances for the club.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/><ref>Frost, p. 385</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/bradfordcity/brad